<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mich. Journalist Cleared of Charges  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALDWIN, Mich. (AP) -- A former newspaper editor who was fired
after allegedly leaving obscenity-laced threats and ethnic slurs on
a black township official's answering machine has been acquitted of
a felony count of ethnic intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   Roger ''Bucky'' VanderMeer, 55, was acquitted by a jury of 11
whites and one black on Tuesday, despite acknowledging that he had
left the messages on the answering machine of Yates Township
Trustee Donel Brown. A judge tossed out a misdemeanor count of
making a threatening telephone call.
</P>
<P>
   VanderMeer was fired as editor of the weekly Lake County Star on
June 14, one day before he was arraigned on the charges. He said he
had been angry at Brown because Brown had scolded VanderMeer's
wife, Pam, the township's clerk.
</P>
<P>
   ''He got drunk that night because he'd had enough,'' said John
Beason, VanderMeer's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Beason told the jury that VanderMeer was so intoxicated that he
could not possibly have carried out his threats, left in a series
of four messages.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first time I heard the recording was in court,''
VanderMeer said in Friday's editions of The Grand Rapids Press. ''I
can't believe I said that. I must have been out of my mind. I'm
married to a black woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he wonders what message the acquittal sent to this
ethnically diverse community 70 miles north of Grand Rapids.
</P>
<P>
   ''In his message, he said he, as a white man, was one of the
people who is allowed to do anything he wants and I, as a black
man, can do nothing about it,'' Brown said. ''At this point, I
would say he was right. It appears to me that Bucky VanderMeer is
the one with the real power in Lake County.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
