<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 00:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Celebrities Join Human Rights Drive  </HEADLINE>
By CARL HARTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- She is one of the lesser-known heroes. But her
eyes and the set of her jaw reflect the strength and determination
that earned her a place with better-known fighters for human rights
-- people like Archbishop Desmond Tutu of South Africa and former
President Oscar Arias of Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   Digna Ochoa of Mexico is a Roman Catholic nun and human rights
lawyer. She knows the torturer's touch and the threats against
family and friends. She is one of 51 people from 40 countries
portrayed in the book, ''Speak Truth to Power.''
</P>
<P>
   Written by Kerry Kennedy Cuomo, with photographs by Pulitzer
Prize winner Eddie Adams, the book profiles human rights activists
to disprove what Cuomo calls ''the lament that there are no more
heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of the late Robert F. Kennedy and the wife of
Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo, she hopes the book will focus
renewed attention on people who risk their lives for others.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a mother of three young girls,'' she wrote, ''I deeply
wished to understand of there were steps I could take to encourage
my own daughters to develop similar attributes or if moral courage
was something certain people are born with.''
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Ochoa tells how her father, a union leader, was
kidnapped and tortured. Years later, when she was a human rights
activist she was held by police.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now I felt in the flesh what my father had felt, what other
people had suffered,'' she said. For a month she was tortured with
electric shocks. Mineral water was pumped up her nose.
</P>
<P>
   She escaped, went into hiding and finally was able to resume her
human rights work. Cuomo went to Mexico to interview Ochoa last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just a few weeks after this interview,'' Cuomo wrote, ''two
men assaulted her in her apartment. They blindfolded her, tied her
up, interrogated her, threatened her and pressured her to sign a
statement. They cut her phone line and opened a gas valve in a
closed room. Her attackers left files stolen a few months
earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Ochoa was defending two environmentalists accused of belonging
to guerrilla groups when the threats against her intensified. In
August, she came to Washington. ''But only temporarily,'' she said
in an interview. ''My commitment is to human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican government, she said, has only complied in part with
requests from the Inter-American Court for Human Rights to
guarantee her security and that of her organization, a Catholic
human rights group.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 28, the day she arrived in Washington, a Mexican court
sentenced her clients to six and 10 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International and Mexico's Human Rights Center say
police brutally tortured them in efforts to get confessions.
</P>
<P>
   She said she did not know how long she would stay in the United
States, which she has visited before. A new government, Mexico's
first takeover by an opposition party in 70 years, will be sworn in
Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can only hope,'' Ochoa said. ''There has to be a change, at
least a change in personnel.''
</P>
<P>
   Few people have heard of Juliana Dogbadzi of Ghana, also
interviewed by Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I was 7 years old,'' she said, ''my parents took me from
our home and sent me to a shrine where I was a slave to a fetish
priest for 17 years ...''
</P>
<P>
   ''I lived and worked in the priest's fields and kept the
compound clean. While doing so I was raped repeatedly by the priest
on torn mats on the cold floor of windowless huts ...,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The book says that in 1997 approximately 5,000 girls and young
women were kept in 345 shrines in southeast Ghana.
</P>
<P>
   Dogbadzi escaped on her fourth attempt after a man from an
organization called International Needs-Ghana came to the shrine
and spoke to the priest. She reached the organization's
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now that I have escaped,'' she said, ''I help to diminish the
women's fears by telling them my story ... I try to help the
priests to understand the pain that the women have endured.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On The Net:	   www.SpeakTruthtoPower.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-16-00 0053 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000916.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 00:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aussies Top Kazakstan in Water Polo  </HEADLINE>
By PETE IACOBELLI
<TEXT>
<P>
   RYDE, Australia (AP) -- There's no crying in water polo. Except
for this match, an Olympic first.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never get emotional, I didn't think I would,'' said
Australia's Bridgette Gusterson. ''I never cry before a game. I did
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Gusterson scored three goals as Australia defeated Kazakstan 9-2
Saturday (Friday EDT) to open the first Olympic women's water polo
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ''For me it was an absolute experience,'' said Australia's
Debbie Watson, who is 35 and unretired to take part in history. ''I
feel very lucky to have been here.''
</P>
<P>
   Australia, one of the favorites in the six-team tournament, got
two first-half goals from Gusterson. Yvette Higgins added two for
Australia, which should get a tougher game from Russia on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But the game was as much a celebration for Australia, serving as
host to the first women's tournament in a sport that that has been
men-only at the Olympics since its debut in Paris a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams stepped into the pool while a Shania Twain recording
said, ''Let's go girls'' and fans clapped along.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wasn't sure there would be anybody here,'' said Higgins, at
22, one of the team's youngest members.
</P>
<P>
   Boy, was she wrong.
</P>
<P>
   There were about 4,000 people at the Ryde Aquatics Leisure
Center. About 50 of them wore green and yellow frizzy wigs with
shirts saying ''Giddy Up, Aussies,'' on the front and ''Australian
Women's Water Polo Olympic Cheer Squad,'' on the back. They broke
into Aussie chants and sang ''Waltzing Matilda'' as their team took
control.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, the crowd stood and cheered. Players from both
teams waved back.
</P>
<P>
   Kazakstan led 1-0 on Olga Lechshuk's goal only 45 seconds into
the game. That would be one of Kazakstan's few highlights.
</P>
<P>
   ''We started very strong in the first quarter, which we knew we
had to against Australia,'' said Rezeda Aleyeva of Kazakstan.
''Once we found the first goal, we knew we had to keep at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Australia wouldn't let them.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins tied the game four minutes later and Gusterson put
Australia ahead for good on a penalty shot with 1:53 left in the
first period.
</P>
<P>
   Kazakstan had chances to get back in it. But goalkeeper Danielle
Woodhouse, a second-half replacement for Liz Weekes, made several
close-in stops to keep Kazakstan off the board during the final two
periods.
</P>
<P>
   Watson embraced teammates at the final horn. She remembered how
she was certain, after being told other sports would have to
downsize to get her sport in, that she'd never compete beneath the
Olympic rings. ''We heard maybe in '84 or '88, then '92 and '96,''
she said. ''I didn't think it would happen for me.''
</P>
<P>
   When she learned in 1998 that her homeland would be the host,
she dragged herself back into a sport she left about 2&AMP;frac12; years
earlier and earned a spot.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's good that we could do this,'' said Gusterson, the team
captain, hugging her friend Watson.
</P>
<P>
   Australia coach Istvan Gorgenyi said his team's slow opening
probably stemmed from the emotions. ''It made things very
nervous,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he was glad when his team got rolling. ''It's good they
could play in this game,'' Gorgenyi said. ''Now we can concentrate
on tournament.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
