<HEADLINE> Bush, Gore Camps To Meet on Debates  </HEADLINE>
By DOUGLAS KIKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Officials from Al Gore and George W. Bush's
presidential campaigns are meeting to complete a draft deal that
sources close to the negotiations say features three debates -- one
traditional two-lectern event, one town hall, and one ''talk show''
forum.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Democrat Gore were willing to accept the three-format
plan, which the bipartisan Commission on Presidential Debates
proposed in January. Republican Bush had earlier balked at both the
suggested formats and the commission's three-debate schedule, but
bowed to the plan after coming under criticism.
</P>
<P>
   The two campaigns, after meeting 7&AMP;frac12; hours on Friday, broke to
review the proposal before meeting again Saturday to work out
details and sign off on the formats, said one source, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Details still under discussion include the amount of time for
questions, responses, counter responses and whether these times
should vary based on format, this source said.
</P>
<P>
   A Bush campaign official, also demanding anonymity, confirmed
the two sides had tentatively agreed on the three-format plan and
were waiting to see the details in writing.
</P>
<P>
   Neither campaign would comment on details of the debate
negotiations, but both sides sounded optimistic the deal would be
done soon.
</P>
<P>
   There was ''substantial progress made toward an agreement,''
Bush campaign chairman Don Evans said through a spokeswoman. Gore
campaign chairman William Daley also was in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Quinn, a spokeswoman for the Democratic National
Committee, said the Gore campaign went into the talks ''ready to
take the commission mix.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush had pushed for more informal debate formats and said nearly
two weeks ago said he would accept only one commission debate and
two networks debates -- one on NBC and another on CNN's ''Larry King
Live.'' Gore rejected Bush's idea.
</P>
<P>
   Bush gave in on Thursday and agree to the three commission
debates.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Fahrenkopf, the Republican co-chairman of the debate
commission, said after Friday's session, ''Different formats have
different dynamics to go along with it, and that is what we are
trying to iron out.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kirk, his Democratic counterpart, said, ''Ninety-five
percent of the issues are agreed upon. ... Great strides were
made.''
</P>
<P>
   The presidential debates are to be held Oct. 3 in Boston, Oct.
11 in Winston-Salem, N.C., and Oct. 17 in St. Louis, with each
lasting 90 minutes starting at 9 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   A 90-minute debate between the vice presidential candidates,
Democrat Joseph Lieberman and Republican Dick Cheney, will go take
place Oct. 5 in Danville, Ky. All the debates are on college
campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party nominee Pat Buchanan and Green Party nominee Ralph
Nader, both registering single digits in national polls, most
likely will not meet the commission's threshold of 15 percent in
media polls for inclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan lost a legal battle to enter the debates in a ruling
released Friday. U.S. District Court Judge Richard Roberts rejected
Buchanan's claim against the Federal Election Commission for
dismissing his complaint against the debate commission concerning
the 15 percent threshold.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's agreement to have the debates under the commission's
sponsorship ended a standoff lasting several weeks in which Bush
held out for doing only one debate sponsored by the commission and
less-formal matchups in other venues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-16-00 0054 </TRAILER>
