<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, Sept. 16, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Olympics Open With a U.S. Gold
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- American Nancy Johnson captured the first gold
medal of the Sydney Olympics, firing her way to victory Saturday (Friday night
EDT) in the women's 10-meter air rifle. Johnson, a two-time Olympian from
Downers Grove, Ill., hugged her coach and pumped her fists after winning; her
dad, Ben Napolski, was in the audience. The silver medal went to Kang Cho-hyun
of South Korea, and Gao Jing of China took the bronze. Johnson's gold medal
triumph came just hours after the extravagant four-hour opening ceremony.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Philippine Military Attacks Rebels
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ZAMBOANGA, Philippines (AP) -- Military planes and helicopter gunships
pounded rebel camps in the southern Philippines Saturday, in a surprise attack
aimed at rescuing 19 foreign and Filipino hostages. Thousands of troops and
elite police arrived on ships to join the fight in the hills of Jolo island.
People stood in the streets of Jolo's capital watching the distant attack,
marked the bombing sorties by air force planes. On Friday night, the military
ordered all boats to leave the capital's port to clear the way for the arrival
of military ships. Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado said President Joseph
Estrada would make a statement later in the day.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Florence Prompts Bermuda Warnings
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- A hurricane warning was posted in Bermuda late Friday as
Hurricane Florence regained strength and speed as it turned away from the U.S.
mainland and moved toward the Atlantic island. At the same time, a storm system
in the Gulf of Mexico grew into Tropical Storm Gordon, prompting a hurricane
watch for Florida's west coast from Bonita Beach to the Suwanee River. That
storm, packing top winds of 60 mph, could become a hurricane by Saturday night,
according to forecasters at the National Hurricane Center in Miami. It dumped
heavy rain Friday on Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula and caused street flooding in
the resort city of Cancun.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush, Gore Agree on Debate Formats
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Officials close to negotiations said Democrat Al Gore and
Republican George W. Bush tentatively agreed today on three debate formats --
one traditional two-lectern event, one town hall, and one ''talk show'' forum.
The two campaigns, after meeting 7&AMP;frac12; hours, planned to meet again Saturday
to complete details and sign off on the formats, said one official close to
debate negotiations.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
N. Korea: Goodwill Begets Goodwill
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- North Korea said Friday that it will welcome any U.S.
goodwill gestures, now that the two nations have resolved a diplomatic flap over
the recent body searches of North Korean delegates..S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright sent a message of regret to North Korea, explaining that the
search in a German airport by American Airlines security personnel did not
reflect U.S. policy. North Korea's No. 2 leader Kim Yong Nam and his delegation
returned to Pyongyang after the incident, skipping last week's Millennium
Summit. North Korean officials denounced the U.S. action but later said they
took note of the American apology.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Army To Release Kosovo Report
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Army is preparing to publicly release an investigative
report saying several members of the 82nd Airborne Division on peacekeeping duty
in Kosovo beat, threatened and assaulted civilians, officials said. The formerly
classified report also raises questions about the kinds of training these men
received for peacekeeping, the officials said. They discussed the matter on
condition they not be identified.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 160; Nasdaq Sheds 79
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue chip and tech stocks fell sharply today. The Dow closed
down 160.47 to 10,927.00. On the NYSE, losers led gainers by over 5-to-3. The
Nasdaq was down 78.63 at 3,835.23.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Swiss Wins Gold Medal in Triathlon
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Switzerland's Brigitte McMahon outswam the sharks,
bicycled with the pack and outsprinted the field to win the inaugural Olympic
women's triathlon. McMahon, 33, ran away from Australia's Michellie Jones in the
final stretch Saturday (Friday night EDT) to win gold in 2 hours, 40 seconds.
Jones took silver, two seconds behind McMahon, and Switzerland's Magali Messmer
was third.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Blue Jays Beat White Sox 6-5
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Alex Gonzalez and Darrin Fletcher homered off struggling
Chicago rookie Jon Garland and the Toronto Blue Jays continued their strong play
at Comiskey Park, beating the White Sox 6-5 Friday night. In a meeting of MVP
candidates, Toronto's Carlos Delgado walked twice and was hit by a pitch in an
0-for-1 night while Chicago's Frank Thomas was 0-for-4 with a walk. Toronto
drove Garland (3-7) out in the fifth on run-scoring doubles by Brad Fullmer and
Fletcher that made it 6-2. Fletcher hit a solo homer in the fourth, his 18th.
</P>
