<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Official Urges Raising Kursk  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- A senior Russian government official insisted
Friday that the sunken nuclear submarine Kursk must be raised to
quell public fears of a future nuclear disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov told the lower house of
parliament that the sub and its reactors could remain on the seabed
for ''decades'' without posing any radiation risks, but must be
recovered to allay public nervousness.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will remain a problem for Russia since it lies in a busy
fishing area,'' Klebanov said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, it is necessary to raise and inspect the submarine
to draw a final conclusion about what caused the disaster, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kursk sank in the Barents Sea on Aug. 12, killing all 118
crewmen aboard. Klebanov, who heads the commission investigating
the catastrophe, has said experts were still considering three
possible versions of the disaster -- a collision with a World War II
mine, a collision with an ''underwater object,'' and internal
malfunctions.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have said that American subs were shadowing the
Russian naval exercise in the Barents Sea, but denied a collision
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Klebanov reaffirmed that next month divers will cut holes in the
sub's hull to remove the bodies of the 118 seamen who died in the
disaster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
