<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jones Ready To Start Olympic Quest  </HEADLINE>
By BERT ROSENTHAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Inspired by the magnificent opening
ceremonies at her first Olympic Games, Marion Jones is eager to
begin her quest for five gold medals, confident she can accomplish
the unprecedented feat.
</P>
<P>
   ''My days are filled with anticipation,'' Jones said Saturday, a
week before she begins competition in her bid to win golds in the
100 and 200 meters, the 400 and 1,600 relay, and the long jump.
''They're not filled with doubts, with hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've had the dreams, the expectations of being on the podium.
I want to have all these dreams realized. I would love for it to
get started.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones has no fears in the 100 and 200, where she has been
dominant throughout the world since 1997. In each of the past three
years, she has been ranked No. 1 in both sprints.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I put together the race I'm capable of, I don't think
anyone can beat me,'' she said. ''I'm confident, I'm 24, I'm at the
top of my game.
</P>
<P>
   ''If someone's going to run 10.5 (seconds in the 100), let's get
out there and race.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one woman has run as fast as 10.5 -- the late Florence
Griffith Joyner, with 10.49, at the U.S. Olympic trials in 1988.
Griffith Joyner also is second and third on the all-time list, with
10.61 and 10.62. Jones is next at 10.65, and has seven of the next
eight-fastest times, with only Griffith Joyner interrupting her
streak at No. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith Joyner also owns the two-fastest times in the 200,
21.34 and 21.56, with Jones third at 21.62.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I step onto the track for the 100 and 200 finals,
wonderful things are going to happen,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   She also is not overly worried about the relays, even though she
hasn't run a 1,600 relay since her sophomore year at North
Carolina. She has anchored several 400 relays over the years and
has the speed to overcome any small deficits.
</P>
<P>
   In the longer relay, her final event, Jones' endurance will be
tested because of her lack of 400-meter experience. She has run
only a handful of 400s in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   If she gets to that point, she feels she'll be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hopefully I will have four gold medals and be going for a
fifth,'' Jones said. ''It may come down to adrenaline. I'm in the
best shape of my life. I'm not worried about fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   The long jump does concern her. It's by far her weakest and most
inconsistent event. In her final long jump competition before the
trials, she finished fifth, and last year, her bid for four golds
at the World Championships ended with a third place in the long
jump.
</P>
<P>
   ''My approach to the board wasn't good,'' Jones said about her
fifth-place finish. ''I've made some corrections. My speed is
there, but it's difficult to adjust my speed to the long jump after
running the 100. I can't run 10.69 down the runway.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm hoping for one big jump -- that's what people are saying. I
need to relax and transfer my speed to the runway.
</P>
<P>
   ''The long jump is special because it's the big question.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past couple of years, Jones' inconsistent performances in
the long jump have resulted in experts offering advice. Jones has
brushed aside all suggestions for help.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm confident in Trevor (coach Trevor Graham), I'm confident
in my abilities,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who bypassed an opportunity to be an Olympian as a 400
relay alternate in 1992 because she wanted a chance to be an
individual gold medalist, made her initial appearance in an Olympic
stadium Friday night for the opening ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was an overwhelming experience, simply incredible,'' she
said. ''Posing with Alonzo Mourning and meeting Venus and Serena
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ''I walked into the stadium and I was overwhelmed how big it
was. It was awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, it will be Jones' turn to perform in Olympic Stadium, and
she's anticipating the moments.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will have my critics,'' she said. ''Some people will say I
can't do it. This is my goal. I'm not here to say I'm Superwoman,
but this is what I want to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   ''No matter what anyone says, it's not going to deter me from
going after five.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is what I've dreamed of.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-16-00 0209 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000916.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sailors Right In the mix in Sydney  </HEADLINE>
By BERNIE WILSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- When they look at the stunning scenery
of Sydney Harbor, Olympic sailors can hardly believe their luck.
</P>
<P>
   They've never had it this good. Normally shunted off to a remote
patch of ocean far away from the host city, they'll be right in the
middle of the action in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   They'll be tacking in front of the Sydney Opera House and its
sail-shaped roofs, with the Harbor Bridge and the skyline adding to
the backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   Red-roofed villas in the eastern suburbs look out over some of
the four harbor courses, and two more courses will be set on the
Pacific Ocean, out beyond the imposing sandstone cliffs of Sydney
Heads.
</P>
<P>
   The ''selling rices'' -- that's how Aussies pronounce ''sailing
races'' -- will be virtually impossible to ignore. Dinghies,
catamarans, windsurfers and the wild-and-wooly new 49er class will
skim across the city's nautical playground, which is one of the
world's most spectacular natural amphitheaters.
</P>
<P>
   ''The harbor is an incredible thing,'' 49er crewman Charlie
McKee of Seattle said in amazement. ''The Olympics are right here
in the middle of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Sydney's signature green and yellow ferries will have to
make way as Olympic sailing is held in a working port for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of spectators can watch from the shore or from boats.
It's only the second time in recent history that sailing has been
visible from the shore at the host city, and even in Barcelona it
was only to a limited degree.
</P>
<P>
   The sailors are here to win medals, of course, and won't care
about the scenery during the races. But they notice it on the way
to and from the courses. Craig Healy, one of two crewmen for
skipper Jeff Madrigali, said it'll be special for the Soling crews
that will match race for the medals off the Opera House.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think on the 30th, whoever's in that top final round, is
going to really have a moment there against that backdrop,'' said
Healy, who like the rest of the Soling crew is from the San
Francisco area. ''It's going to be a fun thing. And the medal
ceremony's there, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Sydney has always been a sailing hotspot, and U.S. team leader
Hal Haenel was stunned by a conversation he had with a cab driver
before a pre-Olympic regatta two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''He saw that I was with U.S. Sailing and said, 'You really
think your McKees have a chance against the Nicholson guy?' I said,
'Do you sail?' And he said, 'No, we just follow it.'
</P>
<P>
   ''You don't get that in the states,'' said Haenel, who won gold
and silver medals while crewing for current Star skipper Mark
Reynolds of San Diego. ''When a cabbie knows the name of one of
your sailors, you know you're in the sailing Mecca.''
</P>
<P>
   Australia's Chris Nicholson won the first three 49er world
championships and, with crewman Daniel Phillips is favored to win
gold here.
</P>
<P>
   In a colorful touch, the billowing spinnakers of the 49ers will
be imprinted with the national flag of the crew.
</P>
<P>
   The 49er competition should be one the highlights. The winged
skiffs, based on the famous Sydney 18-footers, are light and fast,
capable of reaching 25 knots. Attached to safety lines, the sailors
hike, or prop themselves out over the edges of the wings, to keep
the boat level.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's definitely on the edge,'' said Charlie McKee, 38, a
bronze medalist in the 470 class in 1988 who crews for his brother,
Jonathan, himself a gold medalist in the discontinued Flying
Dutchman class in 1984. ''I think that's why we're still in it.
This boat came along and it's like, 'Wow, this is definitely a
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans will try to atone for 1996, when they won just two
bronze medals in their home waters in Savannah, Ga. Those sailors,
Courtenay Becker Dey in the Europe and Madrigali return.
</P>
<P>
   The first races are Sunday (Saturday EDT) for the women's and
men's windsurfing, Soling and the Tornado catamarans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-16-00 0210 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000916.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Wins Gold Medal in Triathlon  </HEADLINE>
By ROB GLOSTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Brigitte McMahon had pictured the scene
many times before, envisioning her run toward the Sydney Opera
House at the end of the inaugural Olympic triathlon. But there was
an added twist when it became reality.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss iron woman outswam the sharks, bicycled with the pack
and then sprinted away from Australia's Michellie Jones in the
final 100 meters to win the women's triathlon Saturday (Friday
night EDT).
</P>
<P>
   McMahon, 33, who took up triathlon after she failed to make the
Olympics as a swimmer, kicked past Jones as the two raced down
Macquarie Street and onto the plaza in front of the opera house.
</P>
<P>
   ''In my mind, in all my hard workouts, I actually pictured those
last kilometers toward the opera house,'' she said. ''I wasn't
picturing myself in the lead, but I pictured myself being happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The men get their chance Sunday (Saturday night EDT), contesting
their triathlon on the same course.
</P>
<P>
   Three-year-old Dominic McMahon was napping in front of the opera
house until the final moments of the women's race. After his Mom
won, he celebrated by playing with a shiny new toy -- an Olympic
gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon won in 2 hours, 40 seconds. Jones took silver, two
seconds behind McMahon, and Switzerland's Magali Messmer was third.
Joanna Zeiger, a doctoral student in genetic epidemiology at Johns
Hopkins University in Baltimore, was fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a totally awesome experience. I don't feel a tiny bit
frustrated (by just missing a medal),'' said Zeiger, who finished
45 seconds behind McMahon. ''I'm so excited and psyched. It was a
great day -- I couldn't be happier.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Taormina, a former waitress from Livonia, Mich., and a
1996 Olympic gold medalist in a swimming relay, placed sixth.
Jennifer Gutierrez, a gym teacher from Denver whose father played
baseball in the Cincinnati Reds' organization, was 13th.
</P>
<P>
   The triathlon started in the shimmering water of Sydney Harbor --
crowded with everything from sailboats to ocean liners, but
apparently no sharks -- and ended on the plaza in front of the
city's landmark opera house.
</P>
<P>
   The running portion of the event turned into a duel down the
stretch between McMahon and Jones, who grew up in the Sydney
suburbs. They broke away from a five-woman pack early on the last
lap, then ran together until McMahon's closing sprint.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was just was too strong. I surged with about 200 meters to
go and she surged and I tried to surge again and my legs just went,
'No,''' Jones said. ''It's going to give me nightmares, but at
least I got a silver medal.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike McMahon, a former triathlete and tennis instructor from
North Sutton, N.H., who has been coaching his wife for the past two
years, said he sought a little help from nature before the race.
</P>
<P>
   ''I went around the 'Wishing Tree' in the park three times
forward and three times backward,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Taormina, an MBA who worked as a Waffle House waitress to
support her athletic career after attending college at Georgia,
finished the swim in 18 minutes, 39 seconds -- giving her a lead of
35 seconds over a pack of four competitors.
</P>
<P>
   She led for the first lap of the bike race through Sydney's
business district, but was caught on the second lap by Germany's
Joelle Franzmann -- who led a pack of 15 athletes through the rest
of the ride.
</P>
<P>
   A five-woman pack broke away from the field on the first of the
two running laps through the Royal Botanic Gardens, where thousands
of fruit bats hang from the trees. McMahon and Jones made their
move on the second lap.
</P>
<P>
   ''I saw it was just Michellie behind me. I said to myself,
'First or second, this is as good as it can be,''' McMahon said.
''I pushed as hard as I could, and it was enough. It's the most
fantastic thing possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Though most of the competitors discounted the chances of a shark
attack, six divers equipped with shark-repelling devices escorted
the triathletes in the 1,500-meter swim through the brisk 61-degree
water of Sydney Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   The race marked the Olympic debut of triathlon, which still has
provisional status as an Olympic event. Triathletes hope the
enthusiasm generated by fans who lined the waterfront and the race
route will help promote their sport.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it was a fantastic day for our sport. I really think
we showed today that triathlon is an Olympic sport,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think people are going to see what happened out there today
and be amazed at this thing called triathlon, where they swim, bike
and run. It's fast, it's furious, that's what makes it so
exciting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-16-00 0217 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000916.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vinson Gives U.S. First Boxing Win  </HEADLINE>
By TIM DAHLBERG
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Winning his first Olympic bout would
have been good enough for Clarence Vinson. But having Muhammad Ali
around to congratulate him made it even better.
</P>
<P>
   Vinson's Olympic boxing debut Saturday was an emotional one from
the time he rode to the arena until Ali greeted him after his win
over France's Rachid Bouaita.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was coming here and I had feelings I never had before,'' the
U.S. 119-pounder said. ''Tears came into my eyes. I'm here at an
Olympics. I never thought I'd get here.''
</P>
<P>
   The moment didn't overwhelm Vinson, though, who trailed after
the first round but scored the last eight points of the fight to
win 9-2 over Bouaita, who was fighting in his second Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Ali, who had entered the arena a few fights earlier, stayed
around to watch Vinson and then came up to him and gestured to the
boxer, as if to say he had done a good job.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was like a dream come true,'' Vinson said of Ali's gesture.
</P>
<P>
   Vinson's win was important not only because it advanced him to a
second round match against Taalaibek Kadiraliev of Kyrgystan, who
stopped Ngoudjo Herman of Cameroon in the third round. It also gave
the 12-member U.S. team a win in the first American fight of the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's going to give the other guys a lot of
confidence,'' U.S. coach Tom Mustin said.
</P>
<P>
   Vinson, who at 5-foot-2 gave away five inches to the Frenchman,
needed to work inside to get his win and he was able to do so after
a round of trying to figure out what to do best.
</P>
<P>
   Bouaita was no slouch, having advanced to the quarterfinals in
the 1996 Games, and took a 2-1 lead after the first round in the
computer scoring that gives points only if three of five ringside
judges agree on a punch that lands.
</P>
<P>
   Bouaita would get no more points the rest of the fight, though,
as Vinson adjusted and pressured his opponent while landing
effectively with left hooks and right hands.
</P>
<P>
   ''The guy was real tall and I felt as though I had a better
chance on the inside than on the outside,'' Vinson said. ''My coach
told me to get in there and be more aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinson, whose uncle, Mark Johnson, is a former IBF junior
batamweight champion, was not considered one of the top American
medal hopes coming into the games. He fights in a crowded division
that features several veteran boxers.
</P>
<P>
   But the energy level at which he fought the final two rounds
gave his coach the hope that high altitude training in Colorado may
pay off in some late round wins for American boxers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first bout gives you the chance to see if all your hard
work paid off,'' Mustin said. ''We're really strong the last two
rounds. I think it's probably because of the altitude training.''
</P>
<P>
   The first session of boxing at the Sydney Exhibition Center drew
a good, but not capacity, crowd, which witnessed a few new twists
in a sport that struggles with its image in the wake of some
Olympic boxing scandals.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, boxers fought four, 2-minute rounds instead
of three rounds at three minutes. They also fought under new rules
that call for a fight to end early if one boxer is ahead by 15
points.
</P>
<P>
   That happened in the first fight of the day, when Alisher
Rahimov of Uzbekistan landed a few punches at the bell to end the
third round to give him a 17-1 lead and the win over Cho Suk-hwan
of South Korea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
