<BODY>
<HEADLINE> LA Transit Strike Said Inevitable  </HEADLINE>
By JUDY LIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Bargaining between transit workers and the
Metropolitan Transportation Authority came to a halt late Friday
night, with both sides saying a strike appeared inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations broke off between United Transportation Union and
the MTA more than an hour before the union's 12:01 a.m. strike
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will have our strike and we'll come back to the bargaining
table when this negotiating team is ready to bring with them ...
the authority that is needed to sign an agreement,'' James
Williams, president of the union, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   MTA spokesman Mark Littman blamed the union for the impasse.
</P>
<P>
   ''We made concession after concession after concession ... they
just walked out, stranding hundreds of thousands of people. This is
outrageous,'' Littman said.
</P>
<P>
   The strike deadline was originally set for 12:01 a.m. Friday but
the union representing 4,300 bus and rail drivers agreed to a
24-hour delay, and talks continued.
</P>
<P>
   A strike by bus and rail drivers, mechanics and clerks would
affect about 450,000 people who rely on public transportation in a
1,400-square-mile area of Los Angeles County.
</P>
<P>
   Its full impact likely wouldn't be felt until Monday, however,
when the bulk of the transit system's users return to work from the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ''I live seven miles from the hotel and I have no car, not even
a bike,'' said Rosalio Mendiosa, 62, a bus rider who works as a
waiter at the Beverly Wilshire Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Talks began in June when the MTA said it needed to cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   Labor representatives said the MTA has failed to offer an
improved schedule, proposing instead to increase the number of
lower-paid and part-time drivers. Currently, drivers earn an
average $50,000 annually, but can make an additional $20,000 in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 7 percent of commuters in Los Angeles County use
public transit, but those who do often have few alternatives.
Sixty-eight percent have household incomes under $15,000 per year,
and nearly three-quarters of bus riders are black or Hispanic,
according to the MTA.
</P>
<P>
   Riders were worried as the negotiations went on.
</P>
<P>
   ''I blame the MTA for making it a difficult situation,'' said
Shepard Petit, 55, a disabled student who rides the bus to college.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis had urged resolution of differences to avoid
shutting down the nation's second-largest bus system.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people of Los Angeles should not be subjected to gridlock
and lack of public transit because of intransigence on both
sides,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.mta.net
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-16-00 0229 </TRAILER>
