<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 02:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lead Shared at Pa. Golf Tournament  </HEADLINE>
By ROB MAADDI
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAOLI, Pa. (AP) -- Mark Calcavecchia hopes his experience pays
off in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   Calcavecchia, the biggest name remaining after two rounds in the
inaugural Pennsylvania Classic, shot a 5-under-par 66 on Friday to
match Frank Lickliter for the lead at 8-under 134.
</P>
<P>
   ''(At the Air Canada Championship), I thought, 'Well, I'm duking
it out with Chris Riley and Rory Sabbatini. These guys ought to
fall apart any second,''' Calcavecchia said. ''Didn't happen. Maybe
my experience will come into it a little bit more, but, then again,
maybe it won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabbatini won that tournament two weeks ago and Calcavecchia
finished third.
</P>
<P>
   Calcavecchia, the 1989 British Open winner and three-time Ryder
Cup member, puts a familiar name atop the leaderboard in a
tournament missing many of the big names.
</P>
<P>
   None of the top seven money-winners are competing.
</P>
<P>
   ''This week, it might be Chris DiMarco or Frank Lickliter or
me,'' Calcavecchia said. ''A lot of good players are right around --
well, they are all good out here, but still wide open.''
</P>
<P>
   While Calcavecchia chases his first victory of the year,
Lickliter is seeking his first tour victory. Lickliter finished
second to Payne Stewart in the 1999 Pebble Beach National Pro-Am.
</P>
<P>
   ''Basically just made one error, and that was at the very first
hole yesterday,'' said Lickliter, who shot his second straight
bogey-free round.
</P>
<P>
   Lickliter, who missed the cut in his last three tournaments, had
a 67 in the first PGA Tour event in Pennsylvania in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Pate (66) and Chris DiMarco (67) were a stroke behind at
134. Jim Carter shot a course-record 64 to join Australia's Mathew
Goggin (65) and Emlyn Aubrey (71) at 136. Aubrey, the co-leader
after the first round, double-bogeyed his final hole -- No. 9.
</P>
<P>
   ''To do it in the afternoon, that's a little bit more of a
feather in your cap because it had been walked on and stuff,''
Carter said about the record.
</P>
<P>
   Lickliter teed off at 8:14 a.m. EDT and took advantage of the
soft conditions following overnight thunderstorms. He was off the
Waynesborough Country Club course well before the afternoon wind
could affect his game.
</P>
<P>
   ''As long as it keeps blowing, it might be somewhat of an
advantage,'' Lickliter said. ''I can't tell you how great the
greens are here. The golf course is in such wonderful shape. The
fairways are just perfect. And the greens are actually perfect,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Lickliter, 105th on the money list, finished ninth in the
Western Open and Greater Milwaukee Open in consecutive weeks in
July.
</P>
<P>
   Calcavecchia was second in the Greater Hartford Open, and has
seven top-10 finishes this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've had a lot of second-place finishes in my career,''
Calcavecchia said. ''I don't know if it's bad luck or what. Second
is OK, but it's not first. I've bounced back from those things.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMarco, who has two second-place finishes this year, is seeking
his first victory on the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've had a couple seconds. I've been close,'' DiMarco said.
''Hopefully I've learned from those and I'll go out and keep
playing good.''
</P>
<P>
   Pate is looking for his first PGA Tour victory since 1998. He
had one bogey and six birdies, including a 35-footer on No. 15.
</P>
<P>
Divots: Danny Briggs, the co-leader after the first round, fell
into a tie for eighth at 137 after a 72. ... John Daly missed the
cut after his second straight 72. ... Jim Furyk, born in nearby
West Chester, also missed the cut at 144.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
