<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 02:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ivankov Helps Belarus in Olympics  </HEADLINE>
By EDDIE PELLS
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- If fist pumps and high-fives won
Olympic medals, then the U.S. men's gymnastics team would have been
standing on the podium Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   After a satisfying performance in preliminaries, the United
States had reason to believe it could break through when the team
finals roll around and the medal stand is wheeled out for real.
</P>
<P>
   With two of three sessions complete, and the favored Chinese
still to compete, the United States stood in third place,
comfortably in the top six that will make the team finals Monday.
The U.S. team was within 0.925 points of first-place Russia and
0.448 of second-place Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe it's the best team we've put on the floor since
1984,'' team director Ron Galimore said. ''They averaged over 9.5
per routine. That's what you need to challenge. The whole country
should be proud.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States hasn't won a team medal since those 1984
Olympics, and hasn't won one in a non-boycotted games since 1932.
It was 0.923 points out of third at the Atlanta Olympics, the
beginning of the so-called ''Operation Flip-Flop'' program
installed by Galimore and coach Peter Kormann.
</P>
<P>
   A big part of that effort was getting these athletes to work as
a team and show more heart. On the first night on the biggest
stage, the United States responded with gusto.
</P>
<P>
   Top performances from Paul Hamm, his twin brother, Morgan, and
three-time Olympian John Roethlisberger brought spontaneous chants
of ''USA, USA'' from small corners of the SuperDome and giggles of
satisfaction from Galimore, who watched the meet from the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Americans who traveled halfway across the world had
plenty to cheer about.
</P>
<P>
   Roethlisberger raised his fists, then threw a roundabout into
the air after a key performance on the pommel horse worth 9.6
points.
</P>
<P>
   One routine later, the 30-year-old Roethlisberger burst out with
a defiant yell toward the crowd after a perfect twisting double
back-somersault dismount to end his 9.625 rings performance.
</P>
<P>
   On vault, the normally staid Paul Hamm stuck the landing on his
handspring double-front somersault and smiled widely, lifting his
hands in the air, then high-fiving Kormann, who was nearly jumping
out of his shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Five-time national champion Blaine Wilson one-upped that vault --
and Hamm's celebration -- pumping his fists in the air, then jabbing
another toward Kormann in an unusual display of emotion for an
athlete who rarely lets loose on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the best news for a team trying to break through: Wilson,
the country's preeminent gymnast for half a decade, wasn't on top
of his game. The United States didn't use his scores on floor or
parallel bars.
</P>
<P>
   ''All things being said, we can challenge for a medal,'' said
Galimore, who was especially encouraged that the United States had
finished a spot ahead of Japan and two in front of Belarus.
</P>
<P>
   While the Americans were celebrating, the Russians and Ukranians
were showing that this would be no easy task.
</P>
<P>
   Alexei Nemov, who won six medals in Atlanta, was at his usual
showstopping best, working his flairs on the floor exercise like a
break dancer and flipping high above the bars, like a circus
performer on opening night.
</P>
<P>
   Nemov took the lead in three events and was second in a fourth,
a legitimate contender for the all-around title that barely eluded
him in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   European champion Oleksander Beresh led the Ukraine's chase to
the top with a 9.787 on the high bar.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Ivankov of Belarus made his Olympic debut after an
injury-plagued decade and helped his country into fifth place, one
spot behind Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Ivankov was the world champion in 1994 and favored to win the
all-around in 1996, but tore his Achilles' tendon two weeks before
the games and had to wait four years.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel great,'' Ivankov said. ''Finally. Finally. I wait so
long, I work hard and I thought about retiring, but then I came
back. It's a great feeling to be here and start to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   The favored Chinese team didn't compete until the third session,
later Saturday night. Last year's world champions are seeking their
first Olympic gold medal, despite being favored in several Olympics
past. Earlier this week, Chinese team leader Zhang Jian said he was
looking forward to an all-night party ''when we get it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-16-00 0236 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000916.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 02:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Swimming Team Struggles  </HEADLINE>
By DENIS D. GRAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Once a swimming power, China is
struggling to stay afloat.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese failed to place even one competitor in the finals
Saturday at the opening of Olympic swimming.
</P>
<P>
   The dismal performance was epitomized by world record holder
Chen Yan's showing in the women's 400-meter individual medley. Yan,
reportedly in poor health, was 11th in the preliminaries at 4
minutes, 45.65 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Only the top eight advanced to the final.
</P>
<P>
   Five other Chinese swimmers fell short in the prelims, too. The
400 freestyle relay team placed ninth, also missing a spot in the
final, but was nearly three seconds behind eighth-place Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Chinese still have a few good swimmers,'' Singapore coach
Tang Bock said. ''Once upon a time they swept everything, but they
are still a team to be reckoned with.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese -- especially on the women's side -- blazed into the
limelight in the early 1990s, setting a spate of world records.
Nine still stand, including Chen's 3-year-old time of 4:34.79 in
the 400 free relay.
</P>
<P>
   But the sudden, deep cuts of existing records sparked suspicions
that turned out true: The Chinese swimmers were caught in one
doping scandal after another.
</P>
<P>
   Wu Yanyan, world record holder in women's 200-meter medley,
could not make it to Sydney because she's serving a four-year ban
for doping.
</P>
<P>
   Four other swimmers were among 27 Chinese athletes cut shortly
before the national Olympic team was to leave for Sydney. Many of
those who did come are young, untested or in less than peak
condition.
</P>
</TEXT>
