<DOCNO> APW20000916.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 06:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Military Attacks Rebels  </HEADLINE>
By PAT ROQUE
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAMBOANGA, Philippines (AP) -- Thousands of troops and elite
police buffered by helicopter gunships poured onto a remote island
in the southern Philippines Saturday before dawn, moving in to
rescue 19 foreigners and Filipinos held hostage by Muslim rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Navy ships were blockading tiny Jolo island, and the military
had no immediate official word on the condition of the hostages.
Telephone and transportation links to Jolo were cut off.
</P>
<P>
   Abandoning months of negotiations, President Joseph Estrada said
he finally ordered the attack on the Abu Sayyaf after the group
seized three new hostages last weekend. The group claims it is
fighting for an independent Islamic state in the impoverished
south.
</P>
<P>
   ''Enough is enough,'' Estrada said in a nationally broadcast
speech. ''We will not allow kidnappers or other lawless elements to
mock our laws or control our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The military refused to give information about the attack, but
an official who spoke on condition he not be named said there were
unconfirmed military reports that an American hostage, Jeffrey
Schilling, had been killed during an escape attempt Friday and that
12 Filipino Christian evangelists also being held were executed by
a rebel firing squad after the start of the military attack.
</P>
<P>
   The military also received a separate, also unconfirmed report
that two French journalist hostages had escaped, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   A military officer, who also spoke on condition of anonymity,
said by telephone from Jolo that two rebels had been killed and
four were wounded. He also said troops had been able to gain some
territory around the main rebel stronghold but had met some
resistance. Four injured civilians were being treated at a Jolo
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen rebels had been captured, Defense Secretary Orlando
Mercado said.
</P>
<P>
   Military planes and helicopter gunships were continuing to pound
the rebels' camps with bombs and missiles at late afternoon
Saturday. The gunships returned every 30 minutes to Jolo's airport
to reload and refuel.
</P>
<P>
   Estrada cut short a visit to the United States this past week to
deal with the worsening hostage crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ''I made this difficult decision to authorize the military
operations, aware of the grave risks that the hostages and our
soldiers would face,'' Estrada said. ''It has become clear that I
must act and act decisively.''
</P>
<P>
   Villagers streamed into Jolo's capital to flee the fighting,
Mayor Rashdi Abubakar said. Panicked residents crowded grocery
stores and were unable to escape from the island because of the
naval blockade.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, the military ordered all boats to leave the
capital's port to clear the way for the arrival of military ships.
</P>
<P>
   Support for an assault has grown since last Sunday, when a
faction of the Abu Sayyaf abducted three more people from a
Malaysian diving resort -- despite their earlier pledge not to seize
more hostages while negotiations were underway.
</P>
<P>
   The kidnappings also came just one day after the rebels released
four Europeans -- the last foreigners from a group of 21 people
abducted April 23 from another Malaysian resort.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's now the military's show,'' said chief government
negotiator Robert Aventajado. ''I can't do anything more, although
my heart still yearns for the safety of the hostages.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that a government emissary spoke with rebel leader
Ghalib ''Robot'' Andang Friday night and that he was already
frantic because of the military troops nearby.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Mercado said the armed forces were ''like an arrow
drawn against a bow'' waiting for orders to attack.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously the arrow has been released,'' he said Saturday.
''We hope it can find its target.''
</P>
<P>
   The rebels had threatened to attack southern Philippine cities
and to behead Schilling if there was a military assault.
</P>
<P>
   Various rebel factions are holding Schilling, the three
Malaysians, two French journalists, a Filipino captured in April,
and the dozen evangelists.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling, a 24-year-old Muslim convert from Oakland, Calif.,
voluntarily visited an Abu Sayyaf camp on Aug. 28 and was abducted
when the rebels suspected he was a CIA agent, he says. He has
denied working for the CIA.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen said Friday that
the United States hoped the hostages could be released peacefully,
but that a decision on whether to use force was up to the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a spokeswoman for French President Jacques Chirac
criticized the military operation on Saturday, saying it was very
concerned that the move might put the hostages, including the two
French journalists, in danger. The German Foreign Ministry issued a
statement saying it shared the French concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations for the remaining hostages had been suspended
because of fighting among Abu Sayyaf factions over the division of
ransom money from the release of earlier hostages. Negotiators say
more than $15 million in ransom has been paid, about $10 million of
it by Libya for 10 Westerners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-16-00 0654 </TRAILER>
