<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 07:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Kerik reviewing NYPD's anti-drug efforts  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Police Commissioner Bernard Kerik is reviewing
the NYPD's anti-drug efforts, focusing on the spending of tens of
millions of dollars in overtime and the high percentage of minor
arrests being made by narcotics detectives, The New York Times
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   According to unnamed law enforcement officials familiar with the
review, Kerik is concerned that misdemeanor narcotics arrests
outnumber felony arrests by three to one, an indication that a
large number of people charged with drug crimes serve little or no
time in jail, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik, who served in the department as a narcotics detective for
four years, is also reviewing the process by which investigators in
the Narcotics Division are promoted to the rank of detective from
the rank of police officer, the officials told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik has emphasized that he believes a focus on quality-of-life
offenses has helped win record declines in crime, but the officials
told the newspaper he is concerned that some detectives are failing
to produce higher-quality cases, like arresting drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The number of misdemeanor narcotics arrests has been on the rise
for more than five years, and many police commanders say that
pressure within the department to push up arrest numbers has led to
a flood of minor drug charges, The Times reported.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, narcotics misdemeanors have climbed 295 percent,
while narcotics felonies over the same period have decreased 1.1
percent, according to the recently released Mayor's Management
Report. In fiscal 2000, felony arrests for narcotics dropped 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   During the first six months of 2000, Kerik's predecessor, Howard
Safir, spent more than $40 million of police overtime on a special
narcotics enforcement program called Operation Condor, an effort to
turn around the city's rising murder rate, which in 1999 and the
beginning of this year was inching up, The Times said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first three months of this year, Operation Condor put
additional undercover narcotics buy-and-bust teams on the streets
in targeted neighborhoods. Starting in May, the overtime funds were
spent on additional uniformed patrols and quality-of-life
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   In the first six months of this year, the police made 60,950
misdemeanor narcotics arrests and 19,787 felony narcotics arrests,
according to statistics from the state Division of Criminal Justice
Services. During that period in 1999, the police drug arrests
included 39,260 drug misdemeanors and 21,604 drug felonies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-16-00 0717 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
