<HEADLINE> Grenade Launchers Found in Spain  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HERNANI, Spain (AP) -- Police in this Basque town discovered six
grenade launchers Saturday 500 yards from an open air museum that
Spanish King Juan Carlos visited later in the day, said royal
security.
</P>
<P>
   The launchers, tubes placed in the ground to lob grenades, were
deactivated before the king and Queen Sofia inaugurated the open
air Chillida Museum nearby, said security. Spanish Prime Minister
Jose Maria Aznar and German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder were also
to arrive at the museum Saturday afternoon, after the King.
</P>
<P>
   Security didn't immediately blame anyone for the launchers, but
Basque separatists of ETA have used the notoriously inaccurate
devices in previous years on attacks on Spanish security forces.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of police swarmed the area surrounding the museum,
including a hilltop overlooking the grounds where police apparently
found the grenade launchers.
</P>
<P>
   The find comes amid increasing separatist violence and a swift
police crackdown on ETA separatists.
</P>
</TEXT>
