<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jumpers compete in parachuting contest for over-40s  </HEADLINE>
By BRENDAN SCHURR
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSTOWN, N.J. (AP) - Pat Moorehead logs skydives like other
people pile up frequent flier miles. At last count Friday, he'd
jumped out of planes 5,072 times.
</P>
<P>
   The 68-year-old has been feeding his jumping addiction for 33
years. He and hundreds of other skydivers from around the country
are competing here this week in the national Parachutists over
Phorty Society (POPS) championships. The competition ends Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''You don't quit skydiving because you get old, you get old
because you quit skydiving,'' Moorehead, of Long Beach, Calif.,
said, quoting a phrase seen on parachutists' T-shirts and bumper
stickers.
</P>
<P>
   The divers compete in several categories, including who can land
closest to a spot on the ground about as big as a golf ball, and
which teams of four, eight or ten can make the most formations
before landing.
</P>
<P>
   All day Friday, teams of divers practiced their freefall
maneuvers on the ground at Cross Keys Airport, forming circles,
stars and 'X' shapes by holding each other by the arm or leg.
</P>
<P>
   Then they piled into small planes, flew to about 14,000 feet and
jumped out. Divers grabbed onto each other's legs and arms in the
predetermined manner, then switched to the next maneuver, trying to
form as many shapes as they could in 45 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   When they reached 4,500 feet, they separated and each opened
their parachute.
</P>
<P>
   Looking like little kites with GI Joes dangling from them, they
drifted past the clouds and came to their landings.
</P>
<P>
   Moorehead is president of a subgroup of POPS: Skydivers Over
Sixty, or SOS. The group has about 600 members in 17 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Moorehead, a great-grandfather, calls it ''exhilarating.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a T-shirt that says ''Remember when sex was safe and
skydiving was dangerous?'' Moorehead chats amiably with the other
divers.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a lot of camaraderie in this sport,'' he said. ''You
wind up diving with people you don't even know, and sometimes don't
even speak the same language, but it doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if it makes him feel young, he answered, ''Well, I
never felt old yet, so I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   He met his wife, Alicia, on a skydiving trip 16 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'd both sworn off marriage,'' he said, ''we didn't do well
at it. But we sat down on the plane next to each other and we've
been together ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   Alicia Moorehead is past president of the World Parachutists
Over Phorty Society, which has 10,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason so many older skydivers stay with the sport is
technology, Alicia Moorehead said.
</P>
<P>
   No longer do divers use the old, round parachutes. Today they
use rectangular ones that offer much more control.
</P>
<P>
   ''It makes it much more safe,'' she said. ''The round parachutes
pound you into the ground, they're not as maneuverable.''
</P>
<P>
   They also use altimeters that are strapped to their chests to
remind them when to pull the ripcord. And, just in case they
forget, or for some reason are unable to, a sensor in their
backpack will automatically open the parachute when the jumper
reaches a certain altitude.
</P>
<P>
   Technology also has allowed for ultra-lightweight fabrics to be
used in the parachutes. Even the divers' jumpsuits are computer
generated for different weights and sizes.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest skydiver at this competition is 76. Tom Morrison, of
Ambler, Pa., first dove in World War II. But this, he said, is much
more fun.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's enjoyable. We have an exquisite bunch of people in this
sport,'' said Morrison, who has made 8,950 jumps, including one
last year with George Bush to celebrate the former president's 75th
birthday. ''We all share the same unusual activity out here.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no idea when I'm going to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   --:
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.thepops.com/pops.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-16-00 1043 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000916.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 10:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thoughts from 2 miles up: A reporter's first dive  </HEADLINE>
By BRENDAN SCHURR
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOVE WILLIAMSTOWN, N.J. (AP) - I wasn't scared until we were at
the open plane door - looking 13,000 feet down. But then it was too
late to do anything about it.
</P>
<P>
   I had seen what happened to the other people who had just left
the plane. They got snapped away and started falling - fast.
</P>
<P>
   But when my skydiving instructor stepped out, I didn't have any
choice but to go with him, we were harnessed together.
</P>
<P>
   We shot down and were ripped away from the plane. Too scared to
speak, or do anything else, I just watched the clouds zoom by.
</P>
<P>
   For 60 long seconds, instructor Mark Kruse and I fell together,
the wind snapping in our ears. The air, surprisingly cold for a hot
September day, rushed past.
</P>
<P>
   A skydiver with a video camera attached to his head dived with
us to capture my first dive. At one point, he grabbed my hand in a
handshake and spun me around in a gut-wrenching circle. Things seem
to happen faster up here.
</P>
<P>
   I repeated to myself what Kruse had told me before we got on the
plane, ''Just arch your back, breathe and relax.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Skeffington, manager of Freefall Adventures, had given me
about 20 minutes of instruction on the ground on how to position my
arms and how to land, but he and Kruse acknowledged that most
people forget all that when they get up in the air. ''Arch, breathe
and relax,'' I could handle.
</P>
<P>
   The other thing I had to remember - this one rather crucial -
was when to pull the ripcord. Kruse, of course, had his own cord,
but students are supposed to get the feel of pulling their own.
</P>
<P>
   When we reached 5,000 feet, I was to pull the orange handle at
my hip and release the parachute. I checked the altimeter strapped
to my wrist several times, surprised that we weren't there yet.
While I was enjoying the amazing ride, I knew I'd relax a little
once the chute opened.
</P>
<P>
   At just before 5,000 feet, Kruse gave me the OK and I pulled the
cord. The red, white and blue parachute opened with a snap, yanked
us up with surprising force, then settled us into a smooth float.
</P>
<P>
   Kruse gave me a thumbs up, I took a deep breath and enjoyed the
ride - calm, peaceful and beautiful. For five minutes, homes,
trees, baseball fields and golf courses drifted by. Philadelphia,
about 20 miles away, looked like a small town in the distance, and
clouds hugged the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Wanting it to be over and at the same time not wanting it to
end, I reminded myself that this is probably the only time I'll
ever do this. So I tried to soak it all up - the graceful, floating
feeling, the beauty, the serenity.
</P>
<P>
   When we reached 1,000 feet, Kruse let me help steer the rig
toward the landing zone - a gravel 'X' in the middle of a field. We
angled in toward the ground and landed smoothly, but still a
surprising jolt ran up my legs.
</P>
<P>
   Relieved and excited, I felt like I'd accomplished something,
even though all I did was hang on for the ride.
</P>
<P>
   An hour after landing my stomach is still queasy and my legs are
shaking. I'm afraid to eat anything because I can't be sure it'll
stay where it's supposed to.
</P>
<P>
   But somehow, nothing is the same. The sky seems bluer, the
clouds brighter white, the day happier. It's not just relief that
nothing went wrong. It's an intangible - the joy of having taken
that first step out and the peace of being in one piece 13,000 feet
later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-16-00 1043 </TRAILER>
