<HEADLINE> Taiwan Head Urges China Trade Talks  </HEADLINE>
By ANNIE HUANG
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taiwanese President Chen Shui-bian on
Saturday proposed talks with China aimed at ending his nation's
50-year ban on direct shipping links between the rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Chen had offered during March presidential elections to end the
ban. Lukewarm financial markets, bearish in recent months because
of the new government's prolonged standoff with China and the
public's lack of confidence in its economic policies, have added
pressure to deliver on the campaign promise.
</P>
<P>
   ''The normalization of relations must begin with the
normalization of trade ties,'' Chen said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is about time to have direct shipping links, and we must
seriously face the issue,'' he continued. ''We can no longer act as
an ostrich and use national security as an excuse'' to put off
opening the links.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said this week Taiwan will open transportation links
between the outlying islands of Kinmen and Matsu and the Chinese
mainland as soon as December.
</P>
<P>
   But Chen said this would be only a small step in the process to
legalize the small-scale trade that has already flourished between
the outlying islands and China.
</P>
<P>
   Ending the ban on direct shipping links would require
negotiations with the mainland, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hope the Chinese communists can understand that it requires
mutual efforts to break the stalemate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan and China split amid civil war in 1949. Taiwan imposed
the ban on direct links for security concerns because China has
considered the island a breakaway province and has remained
hostile.
</P>
<P>
   But trade has flourished over the past decade, flowing mostly
through Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office in May, Chen has urged Beijing to set aside
its political dispute with Taiwan and discuss any topics of its
choice.
</P>
<P>
   But Beijing distrusts Chen, who in the past had called for
Taiwan's formal independence. It has insisted that dialogue won't
begin until Taiwan acknowledges that it is an inseparable part of
China, a precondition Chen has rejected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
