<HEADLINE> War Crimes Lawyer Pressures NATO  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Carla del Ponte, the chief war crimes
prosecutor for the former Yugoslavia, said Saturday she was losing
patience with NATO's inability to arrest indicted war criminal
Radovan Karadzic.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am effectively losing patience. I say to myself sometimes,
there must be something that they are not telling me,'' del Ponte
said in an interview with Belgian newspaper Le Soir.
</P>
<P>
   Karadzic, accused of masterminding the ''ethnic cleansing'' of
non-Serbs from areas of Bosnia during the 1991-95 civil war, tops
the tribunal's list of wanted war criminals, along with Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Del Ponte told Le Soir that she had doubts as to whether Western
countries were still pursuing the arrest of Karadzic. ''The
political will to arrest him, is it really there? For the time
being Karadzic is the stronger,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Del Ponte said she would like the creation of a special force to
go after indicted war criminals hiding out in Bosnia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. International Criminal Tribunal for the former
Yugoslavia, located in the Netherlands, at The Hague, already has
some 40 suspects in custody. The tribunal has said it is working at
capacity to deal with the cases.
</P>
<P>
   Karadzic has reportedly been sighted near Sarajevo, but
authorities in the Serbian part of Bosnia refuse to arrest him, and
the area is out-of-bounds for international troops empowered to
seize him.
</P>
<P>
   NATO peacekeepers, who previously were reluctant to undertake a
risky arrest operation, have shown greater willingness to carry out
the tribunal's arrest warrants. The alliance has said it aims to
capture all indicted war criminals in both Bosnia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Del Ponte said she would be going to Washington on Sept. 25 to
meet Defense Secretary William Cohen, and other officials to
discuss Karadzic and other fugitives still in hiding.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to know exactly what is being done,'' del Ponte said.
</P>
</TEXT>
