<HEADLINE> GOP Seeks Tax Relief From Surplus  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The projected budget surplus should be used
for tax relief and 90 percent of next year's surplus should go to
pay the national debt, a Republican congressman said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Kuykendall of California said that while a proposed
law to get rid of the so-called ''marriage penalty'' tax died --
President Clinton vetoed it and Congress failed to override the
veto -- Republicans will not give up.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm disappointed that America's working families aren't going
to get much-needed relief from this unfair tax,'' Kuykendall said
in the weekly Republican radio address. ''But we'll be back to try
again next year.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the money set aside this year for marriage penalty
relief will instead be devoted to paying off the public debt,
saying a half-trillion dollars of it has already been paid back.
</P>
<P>
   Kuykendall noted that earlier this week, Republican leaders met
with Clinton, asking him to join Congress in devoting the lion's
share of next year's surplus to debt payoff.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have said the new Republican goal was an abrupt
abandonment of the Republicans' push for big tax cuts, and of GOP
presidential nominee George W. Bush's call for a 10-year, $1.3
trillion tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now, with their 90-10 debt reduction plan, Republicans have
essentially repudiated their own agenda, which they have pursued
vigorously for the last six years,'' House Minority Leader Dick
Gephardt, D-Mo., said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But Kuykendall said the remaining 10 percent can still go to
education and to increase Medicare reimbursements to health
providers. He added a host of other promises, including repealing
the phone tax enacted in 1898, health care tax relief, increased
military spending and the expansion of private retirement plans,
like IRAs and 401(k)s.
</P>
</TEXT>
