<HEADLINE> Nations Urge End to Angola Civil War  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United States, Russia and Portugal
called for stepped-up efforts to end the civil war in Angola and
discussed strengthening sanctions against UNITA rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The three countries, which have been working together to promote
implementation of a 1994 peace accord, did not disclose Friday what
new sanctions they were considering. The United Nations has imposed
sanctions on UNITA's arms, fuel and diamond trade, in an attempt to
strangle its source of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Portuguese Foreign Minister Jaime Gama said that ''for the time
being, we expect that the sanctions against UNITA combined with
tougher regulations for denying the diamond traffic could produce
some effects.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's hope on the UNITA side the option for a political move
will be stronger than the remaining option for residual military
activities,'' he said in an interview Friday. ''That's our goal.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued on the sidelines of the U.N. General
Assembly ministerial debate, the so-called Troika of Observer
Countries on Angola said they continue to believe that only the
1994 peace deal ''will lead to lasting peace and an inclusive
democratic process.''
</P>
<P>
   The accord collapsed in December 1998 after the government and
UNITA resumed fighting a war that began after Angola's independence
from Portugal in 1975. The U.N. peacekeeping force that had been
overseeing the accord, known as the Lusaka protocol, pulled out in
February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But in a first step to restore a U.N. presence in the country, a
30-member U.N. office has been established to focus on humanitarian
assistance and to promote human rights. It will also maintain
liaison with the Angolan government, military and police.
</P>
<P>
   The three countries said in the statement agreed by their U.N.
ambassadors that they remain committed to assisting in the peace
process and would actively cooperate with the U.N. office.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal's Gama cited several ''steps forward'' that have
increased the possibility of peace -- the U.N. role in humanitarian
and human rights issues, a string of recent military successes for
the Angolan government against UNITA, and government preparations
for elections in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's now on the UNITA side to make decisive options,
abandoning the military choice, coming back to the ... Lusaka
agreements, and rehabilitating itself from its past conduct,'' Gama
said.
</P>
<P>
   Undersecretary-General Ibrahim Gambari, a U.N. special adviser
for Africa, said in July that the government's military campaign
and tightened U.N. sanctions on UNITA were beginning to weaken the
rebels' ability to wage war.
</P>
<P>
   He also cited several ''positive'' events indicating that
prospects for an end to the conflict may be emerging.
</P>
<P>
   In June, he said, President Jose Eduardo dos Santos suggested
Savimbi could be pardoned if he surrendered and renounced war. The
president also reaffirmed that the collapsed 1994 peace deal was
still valid.
</P>
<P>
   The Angolan government previously said it would no longer
negotiate with Savimbi because he reneged on the 1994 deal -- as
well as two prior ones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
