<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arrests Intensify in Yugoslavia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- President Slobodan Milosevic's
regime cracked down on opponents Saturday with several more arrests
of opposition activists ahead of this month's national elections.
</P>
<P>
   Three members of the popular, anti-Milosevic student group,
Otpor, were arrested in Belgrade for pasting posters urging people
to vote against Milosevic in the Sept. 24 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Two more Otpor activists were arrested but later released in the
northern town of Subotica near the border with Hungary, the group's
central office said.
</P>
<P>
   A leading human rights group in Serbia, the Humanitarian Law
Fund, said police had beaten two Otpor members Friday for
distributing leaflets and stickers calling for resistance to
Milosevic's regime.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the president's main challenger, Vojislav Kostunica,
said that ''all that is happening now proves that the elections are
already unfair,'' the private Beta news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica has been campaigning across the country as the
presidential candidate proposed by 18 allied opposition parties,
united with the common goal to oust the autocratic president.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we are struggling for is not a revolution, but democracy.
Most of all we need a normal life in a normal country... a
government that will put an end to the sanctions imposed by the
international community and ensure that people can lead decent,
peaceful lives,'' Kostunica said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, 22 opposition activists were arrested in various
towns. Police raided at least two offices of non-government groups,
seizing computers and holding the detainees who were released after
hours-long questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Many fear more, serious violence in coming days. Milosevic, who
tightly controls the country's armed forces as well as the powerful
state media, has showed resolve to stay in power at any cost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
