<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. court: 37 Swiss firms sought protection on slave-labor claims  </HEADLINE>
By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) - Thirty-seven Swiss companies, including some
well-known firms, sought protection from a U.S. court against
lawsuits over possible use of slave labor by German subsidiaries
during the Nazi era, documents disclosed Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A deadline set by the U.S. District Court in Brooklyn prompted
the Swiss firms, most of which previously had been silent on their
possible involvement, to come forward, said a court-appointed
expert.
</P>
<P>
   According to documents posted on the Internet, giant
corporations Nestle, Roche and Novartis told a federal judge that
subsidiaries they owned in Germany or Nazi-occupied areas during
World War II used slave labor.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies said they could rule out any use of slave labor,
but that they were signing up any way. They thus receive protection
against separate U.S. lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland was not only a World War II banking center but also
a manufacturing base that used its neutrality to deal with both the
Nazis and the Allies.
</P>
<P>
   The documents were among the latest additions to an Internet
site that advises Holocaust survivors about progress in their $1.25
billion settlement with Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week the court-appointed expert, or ''special
master,'' Judah Gribetz, recommended on the site that the bulk of
the money should go to Holocaust victims and their heirs who had
claims to deposits in Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
   But Gribetz said former slave laborers - whether or not they
worked for Swiss subsidiaries - should receive between $500 and
$1,000 from the Swiss fund in addition to whatever the obtain from
a German fund.
</P>
<P>
   Gribetz said that would save ''millions'' in administrative
costs and spare the former slave laborers from having to figure out
whether the company they had worked for was Swiss- or German-owned.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was impossible to say how many people had been forced
to work for the Swiss subsidiaries. Initial numbers are low, but an
estimate of 11,000 ''does not appear unreasonable,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling last July, Judge Edward Korman said Swiss companies
which seek releases from slave labor claims should identify
themselves to the court within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   ''Chief Judge Korman's order appears to have prompted a great
many Swiss corporations to examine the slave labor use of their
wartime subsidiaries,'' Gribetz' report said.
</P>
<P>
   It ''clearly contributed to a greater understanding of the scope
of slave labor use by companies owned by Swiss entities,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Gribetz said the Swiss firms that contacted him before the
deadline sought ''releases for themselves and for hundreds of their
subsidiary companies.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The companies writing to the special master included small
businesses bankrupted after the war as well as some of the largest
industrial conglomerates in Switzerland,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The firms include a wide range of industries, especially
manufacturers of pharmaceuticals, aluminum and armaments.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the companies said their records were incomplete for the
era. Others said they did not believe their wartime subsidiaries
used slave labor, but they sought court protection because they
were unable to rule it out.
</P>
<P>
   The food giant Nestle identified seven German plants where it
understood slave labor was used, Gribetz said. Pharmaceutical group
Novartis said it had found two sites owned by its predecessor that
had used slave labor.
</P>
<P>
   Engineering and manufacturing conglomerate ABB Ltd., formerly
known as Brown Boveri and Cie., identified six subsidiaries that
used or possibly used slave labor. The aluminum-manufacturing
Alusuisse Group named five German subsidiaries which ''employed
force laborers assigned to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Nestle has taken the lead in coming forward about the issue. It
said last month it was giving $14.1 million toward the settlement
fund.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is either certain or it may be assumed that some
corporations of the Nestle Group that were active in countries
controlled by the National Socialist (Nazi) regime employed forced
laborers,'' the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Novartis and Roche, another drug manufacturer, said this week
they, too, would each pay $14.1 million into the fund in the
expectation that would cover any possible claims against them.
</P>
<P>
   But, even though they acknowledged slave labor use to Korman,
their press releases earlier this week did not say they knew of any
cases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
