<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Minister Dies in Crash  </HEADLINE>
By NAMINI WIJEDASA
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- A Muslim politician often called the
''kingmaker'' was killed along with 14 others Saturday when a Sri
Lankan air force helicopter crashed into a hill and exploded,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mi-17 helicopter was flying between the capital Colombo and
Ampara, 130 miles to the east, where Ports Minister M. H. M.
Ashraff was to attend election meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Police ruled out the possibility that the helicopter had been
shot down by Tamil rebels, who are fighting to establish a separate
homeland in Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
   ''The probable cause is a technical failure,'' said Commodore
Lal Perera, director of Air Force Aeronautical Engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Just before he boarded the helicopter, Ashraff, 52, wrote a
statement withdrawing his party's legislative support of the
government.
</P>
<P>
   The chopper lost contact with the Colombo control tower and
crashed into a hilly area in Aranayake, 40 miles to the east.
</P>
<P>
   Aranayake police said the fire hampered rescue efforts. The
rescue team traveled by jeep, then walked to the crash site, a
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fourteen bodies were brought to the hospital in a charred
state,'' said Habiba Jabir, medical officer in the nearby Mawanella
district.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being badly burned, she said the minister's body had
been identified by close friends. Only three others have been
identified.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dead were a candidate from Ashraff's party, two
supporters, four security personnel and five crew members. The
identity of the others was not known.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released after his death, Ashraff said: ''From
today, the National Unity Alliance and the Sri Lanka Muslim
Congress disassociate themselves completely (from) the People's
Alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashraff formed the National Unity Alliance Coalition
representing all communities in Sri Lanka, and led its main
constituent, the Sri Lanka Muslim Congress, which he formed in 1981
to represent the country's minority 1.1 million Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   His rise in politics gave the Muslim community more clout in Sri
Lanka. His party has seven seats in Parliament, crucial in a house
where the government has a single-seat majority. Parliamentary
elections are scheduled for Oct. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Ashraff, known as the ''kingmaker,'' pulled back support after a
report in the Daily News quoted D. M. Jayaratne, the general
secretary of the People's Alliance, as saying that the NUA was not
a partner of the ruling coalition.
</P>
<P>
   A former lawyer, Ashraff is survived by his wife Ferial and son,
Aman, 20.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
