<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji Leader Details 'Complexities'  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Fiji's interim prime minister outlined a
schedule Saturday to return the South Pacific island nation to
constitutional rule and urged countries that imposed sanctions
after its May coup to try to understand the ''complexities'' of the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minster Laisenia Qarase devoted almost his entire speech
to the U.N. General Assembly's ministerial debate to explaining the
ethnic makeup of Fiji and the tensions that led to the country's
political crisis earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all live together side by side in Fiji, yet we remain
apart, separated by our ethnicity, religion and cultural
differences and our value systems,'' he said. ''I am committed to
building a united Fiji with a multi-ethnic and multi-cultural
society where all the different communities can live together in
peace, harmony and prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Indians make up 44 percent of the nation's 814,000
population while indigenous Fijians make up 51 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Failed businessman George Speight launched a coup May 19 in the
name of indigenous Fijians, who he said have been marginalized by
economically powerful Fijians of Indian decent.
</P>
<P>
   The coup toppled the democratically elected government of Prime
Minister Mahendra Chaudhry, who was the first ethnic Indian to lead
the country. Speight was arrested July 26, just days after
releasing the last of the hostages he seized after storming
Parliament and taking Chaudhry and others hostage.
</P>
<P>
   Fiji is now ruled by an interim government installed by the
military. Qarase has said his administration will work to redraw
Fiji's constitution to guarantee that indigenous Fijians hold top
political jobs.
</P>
<P>
   He has said he hopes to hold fresh elections in two years and on
Saturday gave a detailed timetable for doing so.
</P>
<P>
   A new constitution will be ready by August 2001, he said, with
general elections to follow within 12 months. A constitutional
commission to draft the new document will be appointed early next
month, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will be representative of all our communities and it will
consult widely throughout the country giving the public at large
every opportunity to submit their advice and recommendations on the
new constitution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Qarase complained bitterly about the sanctions
imposed by Australia, New Zealand, the United States, France and
the Commonwealth on Fiji following the coup, saying they had done
nothing to solve the political crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ''In fact, the very opposite is true; they have only served to
harden attitudes of one community against the other,'' he said. ''I
therefore make a plea to members of the United Nations to show
greater understanding of, and sensitivity to, the complexities of
the situation in Fiji.''
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions include cutting military links, slashing aid,
ending foreign scholarships and banning visits by Fijian sports
teams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
