<HEADLINE> Grandmother of missing N.J. arrested; children recovered  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CLIFTON, N.J. (AP) - The fugitive grandmother of 5-year-old
twins was arrested Friday after returning the children to
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI said Marilyn Parsons, 53, was located in Tijuana,
Mexico, where she had been staying with the twins, Bobby and
Brittany Allison. She had been charged in Clifton with abducting
the children during a court-ordered visitation on Aug. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons' son and the children's mother, Elena Allison, are
separated. Allison was awarded custody of the children, the FBI
said.
</P>
<P>
   William Gore, special agent in charge of the FBI's San Diego
office, said Parsons voluntarily returned to the United States with
the children, where she was arrested on a charge of unlawful flight
to avoid prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons is being held at the Las Colinas Womens' Detention
Center in Sanatee, Calif., where she will await extradition
proceedings to New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The twins were taken to a local children's center pending their
return to New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   They were visiting Parsons at her Dagsboro, Del., home when they
disappeared just days before a court hearing in which Allison was
attempting to have Parsons' visitation rights revoked, claiming the
grandmother was telling the children false stories about her.
</P>
</TEXT>
