<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man accused of warning neighbors of pedophile's placement in group home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WATERBURY, Conn. (AP) - An employee of the Southbury Training
School is accused of distributing the confidential records of a
known pedophile to residents of the community into which the client
was being placed.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Smith, 40, pleaded innocent Friday in Waterbury Superior
Court to a charge of unlawful removal of records.
</P>
<P>
   In an arrest affidavit, authorities claim Smith copied the files
of a 56-year-old mentally retarded man described as ''an
opportunistic same-sex pedophile with a long history of sexually
offending others, including children.'' The client's name has not
been released.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities claim Smith delivered the files to residents and
businesses near the Farmington group home into which the client was
to be placed. The home is located in a residential neighborhood
near two public schools, a day care center and the University of
Connecticut Health Center.
</P>
<P>
   The files included a statement from the client that read, ''When
I get returned, I'm going to get the first kid I see.''
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Mental Retardation blocked the client's
move to Farmington after his records got out.
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary Carpenter, who received copies of the client's
documents in her mailbox June 11, said she's happy to defend a man
she calls ''a hero.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she doesn't know whether Smith distributed the records.
But she's convinced neighborhood children would have been harmed if
homeowners hadn't been tipped off.
</P>
<P>
   ''This person did the right moral thing,'' Carpenter said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is on paid administrative leave from the training school
pending an administrative investigation, director Fritz Gorst said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an unfortunate thing,'' Gorst said. ''The rights of the
individual involved were violated.''
</P>
<P>
   The client is not listed on the sexual offender registry
maintained by the Connecticut Department of Public Safety,
officials said. It was not clear Friday whether the man has ever
been charged with a sex-related crime.
</P>
<P>
   Martin C. Zito, chief of staff for the mental retardation
department, said confidentiality rules prohibit him from discussing
the client's background. He is also forbidden from speaking about
the reasons for moving the client to Farmington, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In general, he said, clients undergo a rigorous review by an
interdisciplinary team before placement in a group home is
considered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
