<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia, Vietnam Flood Waters Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) -- Cambodian troops struggled Saturday
to build a three-mile wall to stop flooding in a northeastern town,
as rising water displaced families and threatened the capital,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 500 soldiers and police were building the sandbag wall
to protect the provincial capital of Kratie, home to 20,000 people,
provincial deputy military commander Lt. Col. Mao Theavy said by
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Water had risen four inches in the last day, he said. The town
lies on the swollen Mekong River about 100 miles northeast of Phnom
Penh, where the speed of the water's rise seemed to be easing,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Flood levels remain about a foot below the point where the
center of Cambodia's capital would be inundated, although some
outlying rural districts were flooded. Home to one million people,
Phnom Penh lies at the confluence of three rivers, including the
Mekong.
</P>
<P>
   Record flooding in Cambodia and Vietnam has affected more than a
million people in recent weeks, killing more than 100 and leaving
thousands homeless, in need of food and supplies.
</P>
<P>
   In Vietnam, floods killed four people in Dong Thap since July
and 11 more, including 10 children, in An Giang province, officials
said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier disaster report found flooding had killed about 94
people in Cambodia since July, when heavy rains began a month-and-a
half ahead of monsoon season.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say the flooding is the worst in 70 years. Weather
forecasters say water levels on the Mekong River have surpassed
that of disastrous 1996 floods that left nearly 200 dead.
</P>
<P>
   Areas of Laos and Thailand have also been flooded. The Mekong
River cuts through or skirts all four countries and feeds numerous
tributaries.
</P>
<P>
   Rice paddies and rural communities in southern Vietnam's Mekong
Delta have become ''desolate lakes,'' the International Federation
of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies in Vietnam said in a report
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Cambodia's King Norodom Sihanouk, who had gone to Beijing for a
routine medical checkup, returned Saturday, a month earlier than
planned.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm in a hurry to meet my compatriots,'' Sihanouk, 77, was
overheard telling Health Minister Hong Sun Huot, one of dozens of
top officials standing in line along a red carpet to welcome him at
Phnom Penh airport.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, wind and rain from Tropical Storm Saomai battered
South Korea's coast Saturday, killing two people and submerging
rice paddies and homes. One elderly man died in a mudslide near the
southern town of Kosung, police said, and another died after being
struck by flying debris in nearby Chinhae City.
</P>
<P>
   Two children were missing after they were swept away in
rain-swollen streams in North Kyongsang Province of central Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   The tropical storm headed out to the Sea of Japan later
Saturday, where its force was expected to further weaken, weather
officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
