<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State police investigating how documents from State Library ended up in Pequot museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - State police have launched a criminal
investigation in an attempt to determine whether documents on
display at the Mashantucket Pequot Museum were stolen from the
archives of the State Library.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation was requested by State Librarian Kendall
Wiggin on advice from Attorney General Richard Blumenthal's staff.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal cautioned Friday that the criminal complaint does not
imply that state officials believe tribal members did anything
illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ''In fact the Mashantuckets may themselves be the victims if
they legitimately purchased documents that had been stolen from the
state archives,'' he said. ''But the theft of that state property
is obviously an extraordinarily serious matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Mashantucket tribal lawyer Patrice Kunesh on Friday called
Wiggin to allow state archivists to examine the documents next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Wiggin has said he is concerned about two Mashantucket-related
records, an 1857 court petition and an 1856 land record.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had sufficient reason to believe that at least one of those
documents may be from our collection,'' Wiggin said Friday. But he
also said the Mashantuckets may have additional documents taken
from the state archives.
</P>
<P>
   Mashantucket officials released a copy of an Aug. 1 memorandum
Wiggin sent to the tribe identifying three collections of documents
at the museum that ''appear to have originally belonged to the
Connecticut State Library.''
</P>
<P>
   The memorandum also raised questions about six other
collections, but Wiggin wrote that ''it is impossible to determine
without direct examination whether or not some may at one time have
belonged'' to the library.
</P>
<P>
   Mashantucket officials said this week they believe they obtained
the 1857 petition around 1992 through a private sale or donation,
but have been unable to locate an invoice.
</P>
<P>
   Under its security procedures, the library should have records
of people who handled the missing Mashantucket-related documents.
Researchers who want to work with archival records must obtain
photo IDs, submit written requests for documents and submit to
searches of their personal belongings.
</P>
<P>
   Library officials tightened procedures in 1980 in response to a
theft of letters from U.S. Marshal W.B. ''Bat'' Masterson, which
were recovered in Colorado by the FBI. It is the last known theft
of documents from the library.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
