<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The gang's all here -- and with it the possibility of brutal crime  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - In the crowd that night were a cheerleader eager
to start college, a math and science whiz, another young man crazy
for sports and girls, and two guys known as regular church-goers.
</P>
<P>
   Stacy Royster and the boys, Robert Savage, Darryl Tyson, James
Stone and Jamel Murphy, were all from nice homes in respectable
neighborhoods in the New York City borough of Queens. The same
words came up over and over to describe the five teen-agers: good,
polite, all-American kids.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors and police charge another word needs to be added
to the list - murderer.
</P>
<P>
   The friends, ages 14 to 17, are accused of viciously beating to
death a Chinese food deliveryman earlier this month after luring
him to a vacant house. According to police, the motive was simple:
they wanted a free meal.
</P>
<P>
   The teens' families and friends are struggling to understand how
these youngsters could have committed the brutal crime.
</P>
<P>
   ''This does not happen here,'' said Savage's neighbor, Troy
McIver.
</P>
<P>
   But it did - just as have other outrageous crimes that produced
big headlines after otherwise normal teen-agers got together as a
group.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's TV movie ''Our Guys'' recalled the tragic 1989 rape
of a mentally retarded girl by four popular high school athletes in
Glen Ridge, N.J. Just last month, seven boys were charged with
brutally beating a man walking home in Tacoma, Wash. They had
apparently grown bored while attending a barbecue, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the phrase ''good kids'' was used for the accused.
</P>
<P>
   So how could they allegedly do such horrible things?
</P>
<P>
   James Alan Fox, a professor of criminal justice at Boston's
Northeastern University, said the teens got caught up in a ''group
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Kids will do things in groups that they will never do on their
own,'' said Fox. ''It's not just that they get caught up in the
moment - it's really that the admiration and the approval of your
peers becomes all-important, more important than the safety of the
victim.''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Sickmund, a senior research associate at the National
Center for Juvenile Justice in Pittsburgh, Pa., said there's often
a diffusion of responsibility in large groups.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's almost like a mob effect - people seem to lose their
minds,'' Sickmund said.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to stop the violence probably never occurred to any of
the youths, Sickmund and Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Being ostracized by your friends, being called a chicken, is
seen as a fate worse than anything the criminal justice system can
mete out,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   And, he added, the teens wouldn't have killed the food
deliveryman because they wanted a free meal. ''It's not satisfying
their hunger that's the motivator - satisfying their need for
approval is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Savage, 14, and Stone, 16, say their clients'
families are in shock, finding it difficult to understand how their
boys could do such a thing. Attorneys for Royster, Murphy and Tyson
- all 17 years old - did not return repeated telephone calls for
comment. The teens' families refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   ''What his parents tell me, he hasn't been a discipline
problem,'' said Rudy Hirschheimer, Savage's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's been no prior problems, nothing like that,'' said
Victor Knapp, Stone's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   To try and understand what happened, Fox said you have to
analyze the teens' friendship.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's the leader who enjoys seeing people do what he says.
And the followers who enjoy being praised,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Richard Bellucci, head of the 113th Precinct's Detective
Squad, said police were still sorting out exactly what happened, so
it's not certain who hatched the scheme to rob Liu on Sept. 1 as
the five teens were hanging out together.
</P>
<P>
   There was Royster, so eager to start college she had already
packed her backpack and set it aside in her bedroom lined with
awards given for her cheerleading at Christ the King High School.
</P>
<P>
   She was introduced to three of the boys by her close friend
Tyson, who couldn't stop talking about sports and girls. Stone and
Murphy are a lot alike - both come from church-going families and
love sports. Murphy spent most of his summer nights coaching a
children's basketball team. Savage was called a smart kid who was
unfailingly polite to adults. Neighbors said he often did errands
for them.
</P>
<P>
   All five had just finished eating Chinese food but wanted more,
and this time they didn't feel like paying for it, said Queens
District Attorney Richard A. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   So they allegedly concocted a scheme to phone for takeout and
have the food delivered to a vacant house, then throw a sheet over
the delivery guy, grab the food and run.
</P>
<P>
   Royster used her cell phone to call the Golden Wok and placed
their $60 order - General Tso's chicken, chicken with broccoli,
shrimp egg foo yong, and shrimp lo mein. The teens grabbed a sheet
and - in case the deliveryman struggled - armed themselves with a
few bricks, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Around 11:30 p.m., Sheng Jin Liu arrived in his car. The
44-year-old Chinese immigrant owned the restaurant and made the
deliveries, while his wife and two teen-aged children did the
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Royster met him near his car. The four boys appeared and
allegedly threw the sheet over Liu's head. Then the beating began,
said Deputy Chief Patrick Timlin, head of the Queens detective
bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Liu was punched and kicked. Police said that Savage - the
youngest and perhaps the most in need of peer approval - picked up
a brick and hit Liu in the head. The teens then grabbed one of the
two bags of food and ran off.
</P>
<P>
   They ate the food at Tyson's house. The other bag of food was
nibbled on by neighborhood cats.
</P>
<P>
   Liu's wife called police when he didn't return, and officers
found him quickly by simply tracing the delivery order to the crime
scene. But when they arrived, Liu was already dead.
</P>
<P>
   Police cracked this case nearly as quickly by analyzing
telephone calls to the restaurant. One was traced back to Royster's
cell phone. Four days after Liu was killed, all five teens were
arrested at their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Each was charged with the same offenses: second-degree murder,
robbery and criminal possession of a weapon. All remain behind bars
without bail. Because of his age, Savage faces a maximum sentence
of nine years to life in prison if convicted. The other four face
up to 25 years to life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-16-00 1328 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000916.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Troops Mass on Island  </HEADLINE>
By PAT ROQUE
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAMBOANGA, Philippines (AP) -- Thousands of Philippine troops
pursued fleeing Muslim rebels Saturday and helicopter gunships
strafed their hide-outs from the air. The fate of their 19
hostages, including an American, was unclear.
</P>
<P>
   The military imposed a news blackout after the surprise attack
aimed at rescuing the hostages held in a remote jungle on Jolo
island. Authorities launched the attack before dawn Saturday
following nearly five months of negotiations with Abu Sayyaf rebels
and the reported payment of more than $15 million in ransom for
other captives.
</P>
<P>
   President Joseph Estrada said his patience broke after the
rebels, who claim they are fighting for an independent Islamic
state in the southern Philippines, seized a new group of hostages
from Malaysia on Sept. 10.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have exhausted all efforts toward a negotiated
settlement,'' he said in a nationally televised speech. ''We will
not allow kidnappers or other lawless elements to mock our laws or
control our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   France, Germany and Malaysia expressed concern about the
decision to attack the rebel camps, saying it could endanger the
lives of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Various Abu Sayyaf factions are holding an American Muslim, two
French journalists, three Malaysians, a Filipino captured in April
and 12 Filipino Christian evangelists.
</P>
<P>
   A military officer on Jolo said two rebels were confirmed dead
and four injured in Saturday's fighting, but there were no reports
of military casualties. Five injured civilians were being treated
at a Jolo hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado said 17 rebels were captured.
</P>
<P>
   The military was checking unconfirmed reports that the American,
Jeffrey Schilling of Oakland, Calif., was killed during an escape
attempt Friday and that the evangelists were executed by a rebel
firing squad after the military attack began, an official said. The
military also was trying to verify a report that the two French
journalists had escaped, said the official, who spoke on the
condition he not be named.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels had earlier threatened to attack southern Philippine
cities and behead Schilling if troops launched an attack.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone and transportation links to Jolo were cut, isolating
panicked villagers who streamed into the island's capital and
snapped up goods in crowded grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   Support for a military assault has soared since the rebels
abducted three more people last week from a Malaysian diving resort
-- despite their earlier pledge not to seize more captives while
negotiations were underway.
</P>
<P>
   The kidnapping came just one day after the rebels released four
Europeans -- the last foreigners from a group of 21 people abducted
April 23 from another Malaysian resort.
</P>
<P>
   Estrada, who cut short a visit to the United States to deal with
the crisis, said the continuing abductions showed the Abu Sayyaf
were ''plain terrorists and bandits.''
</P>
<P>
   The military had prepared for weeks for an assault on the rebel
camps. On Friday, Mercado said the armed forces were ''like an
arrow drawn against a bow'' waiting for orders to attack.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously the arrow has been released,'' he said Saturday.
''We hope it can find its target.''
</P>
<P>
   French President Jacques Chirac criticized the assault, saying
he was concerned it might put the French journalists in danger.
</P>
<P>
   ''The safety of Roland Madura and Jean-Jacques Le Garrec is
France's only priority, and we consider the Philippines responsible
for this,'' Chirac's spokeswoman, Catherine Colonna, said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The French Defense Ministry was in contact with Philippine
military leaders, and Defense Minister Alain Richard asked his U.S.
counterpart, William Cohen, to convey France's concerns over the
safety of the hostages to the Philippine government.
</P>
<P>
   During a visit to Manila on Friday, Cohen had said the United
States hoped the hostages could be released peacefully, but that a
decision on whether to use force was up to the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said he
was concerned about the safety of the Malaysian hostages, but that
''what the Philippine army does against separatist groups or those
out to create chaos in the country is its own responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Philippine presidential spokesman Ricardo Puno echoed that
sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a matter that the Philippines has to decide on its
own,'' Puno said. ''Because after all, when the French leave, we
will be left with the problem here in our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations for the remaining hostages had been suspended
because of rising tensions among Abu Sayyaf factions over the
division of ransom money from the release of earlier hostages.
Negotiators say more than $15 million in ransom has been paid,
about $10 million of it by Libya for 10 Westerners.
</P>
<P>
   Critics had warned that large ransom payments would encourage
new waves of kidnappings in the troubled southern Philippines, home
of the country's Muslim minority.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-16-00 1338 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000916.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Troops Hit Rebel Hid-Outs  </HEADLINE>
By PAT ROQUE
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAMBOANGA, Philippines (AP) -- Thousands of Philippine troops
pursued fleeing Muslim rebels Saturday and helicopter gunships
strafed their hide-outs from the air. The fate of their 19
hostages, including an American, was unclear.
</P>
<P>
   The military imposed a news blackout after the surprise attack
aimed at rescuing the hostages held in a remote jungle on Jolo
island. Authorities launched the attack before dawn Saturday
