<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-CT--Ross-Death Penalty, Conn Bjt,600  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pro forma execution date for serial killer Michael Ross has
come and gone, with no clear schedule in sight for his appeal
before the Connecticut Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Ross' defense lawyers are still waiting for thousands of pages
of transcripts that record every minute of his monthlong death
penalty hearing, from the individual questioning of jurors to the
judge's sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are long periods of time in appeals when nothing
happens. This is one of those times,'' said public defender Mark
Rademacher, who is helping handle the mandatory appeal.
</P>
<P>
   When Ross got six death sentences in May, New London Superior
Court Judge Thomas P. Miano set Sept. 15 as the execution date. But
that date was delayed by an automatic appeal.
</P>
<P>
   So far, defense lawyers have notified the court only that they
plan to appeal based on alleged errors in the way Miano handled the
case. More specific points for appeal will have to be filed later.
</P>
<P>
   The transcripts are expected to be complete by December at the
earliest. Defense lawyers then comb through the official record to
find any fault that the high court may see as grounds to grant Ross
a new trial or life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''In capital cases, they generally throw everything in -
including the kitchen sink,'' said Senior State's Attorney Tim
Sugrue, who has represented the state in previous Ross appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers, however, sometimes point out significant errors
that spare the criminal's life.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Johnson had his death sentence overturned in the 1991
killing of State Police Sgt. Russell Bagshaw. The Supreme Court
found Johnson should get life in prison because his crimes did not
meet the ''especially heinous, cruel or depraved'' standard that
would warrant an execution.
</P>
<P>
   Ross' original death sentence from 1987 was overturned on appeal
and a new penalty hearing was ordered because information that
might have helped make the case for a life sentence was withheld
from the defense.
</P>
<P>
   After the new penalty hearing last winter, a jury decided Ross
should get six death sentences for killing 14-year-old friends
April Brunais and Leslie Shelley, and for raping and killing Wendy
Baribeault, 17, and Robin Stavinsky, 19, in New London County in
1983 and 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Ross' trial lawyer, Barry Butler, said he counted at least 51
appealable issues during the penalty hearing, including motions
about testimony and evidence that the judge denied.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any denied motion is grounds for an appeal,'' Butler said.
''In Connecticut, we don't execute people until the Supreme Court
reviews it - and that's a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parents of Ross' victims have said they hope the appeal and
execution is carried out quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Ross already is serving two life sentences for killing Debra
Smith Taylor, 23, and Tammy Williams, 17, in Windham County in
1982.
</P>
<P>
   Ross previously had said he did not want any non-mandatory
appeals to be filed, to spare his victims' families more pain. He
once tried to go straight to his execution by signing a deal with
prosecutors - a deal that Miano rejected.
</P>
<P>
   When he was sentenced to death again in May, he said he would
allow his lawyers to pursue the appeals necessary to finish the
legal process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-16-00 1345 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000916.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> In first major American show in decades, Met explores pivotal time for New York </HEADLINE>
By KATHERINE ROTH
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Strolling through the Metropolitan Museum of
Art's first major American exhibit in three decades is an
awe-inspiring journey through the rise of money, power and
creativity in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ''The second quarter of the 19th century was an amazing time in
this city,'' said Catherine Hoover Voorsanger, who organized the
show with John K. Howat. ''The New York we know today was really
created during this period.''
</P>
<P>
   But ''Art and the Empire City: New York, 1825-1861,'' which
opens Sunday and runs through Jan. 7, 2001, is also about much more
than the city itself.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is about the art history of this country as seen through
the lens of New York, which becomes the cultural and commercial
capital of the country during this time period, and the largest
city in the Western Hemisphere,'' Voorsanger said.
</P>
<P>
   She said it is the first American exhibit of its size at the
museum since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The show covers the time between the completion of the Erie
Canal and the start of the Civil War, an era when artists first
found they had to come to New York if they were going to be truly
successful, and when the term ''shopping'' was coined.
</P>
<P>
   Lord &AMP; Taylor opened in 1826, Tiffany's (then known as Tiffany
and Young) opened in 1837 and Central Park opened in 1859 (the Met
itself was formed in 1870). The Associated Press and The New York
Times were both founded during this period.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's as obvious as the nose on our face. New York was the
center of things starting from 1825. But it's a period that's
really been overlooked,'' Voorsanger said. ''The density of
material is staggering.''
</P>
<P>
   The show is ambitious and there's a lot to cover, a testimony to
the wealth and creative energy of the period. It took five years to
organize the exhibit, during which time a wish list of over 1,000
works was honed down to 310 gems from 84 lenders in the United
States and Europe. Many of the pieces have never before been on
public display.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit is accompanied by a catalog of the same name, with
hundreds of color illustrations and text by more than a dozen
writers.
</P>
<P>
   Opening with a replica of the Battery Park boardwalk - complete
with a couple dressed up for a 19th-century stroll, ''Art and the
Empire City'' is divided into a dozen galleries organized
thematically within a chronological framework.
</P>
<P>
   It all starts with art works surrounding the 1825 competition of
the Erie Canal, which established the city as the gateway to the
West. Highlights include a full-length portrait of the Marquis de
Lafayette, much beloved at the time for his role in the
Revolutionary War, by Samuel F.B. Morse (on loan from City Hall),
and a pair of monumental silver vases given to Gov. De Witt Clinton
for his role in envisioning and overseeing the building of the
canal.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes a portrait gallery that recalls the Governor's Room
in City Hall as it looked around 1825. It is a window into the
important personalities of the time: Alexander Hamilton, the
nation's first treasury secretary, painter John Trumbull, President
Andrew Jackson, poet and newspaper editor William Cullen Bryant and
author Washington Irving.
</P>
<P>
   Next is a gallery on neoclassical architecture, with
architectural drawings and a facade from the Branch Bank of the
United States. And the fourth gallery, with furnishings dating from
1830 to 1845, gives the feel of one of the period's upscale homes.
Besides stunning ceramics, glassware, silver and furnishings, it
includes pilasters - rectangular supports or columns - and a
mahogany door from a grand Grecian-style house built in Brooklyn in
the 1830s.
</P>
<P>
   Also examined is the interrelationship between the visual arts
and literature - including masterworks like Thomas Cole's 1825
painting, ''Last of the Mohicans,'' inspired by the James Fennimore
Cooper novel.
</P>
<P>
   And one gallery exploring connoisseurship and art collecting
shows some of the works that 19th century city dwellers would have
appreciated at a time when top quality foreign art works were on
public display or were acquired by wealthy New Yorkers for their
private collections.
</P>
<P>
   In the next is a sampling of works and displays seen in 1853 at
a major fair in The New York Crystal Palace, housed in a grand
building of cast-iron and glass in midtown Manhattan which stood
where Bryant Park, alongside the New York Public Library, is now
located.
</P>
<P>
   In counterpoint to the portrait gallery at the beginning of the
show, the gallery on ''Photography, the New Medium'' shows early
New York daguerreotypes and paper prints. Suddenly, this new style
of portraiture becomes accessible for anyone from the illustrious
P.T. Barnum and Walt Whitman to a fireman (who poses with hat and
horn) and a grocery boy with his parcel. There are even a few of
the earliest art photos, which look startlingly contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Great Emporium'' raises thoughts of window shopping on
Madison Avenue or Fifth Avenue and shows what made some of the
city's first shopaholics drool. There are elegant gowns and
gleaming silver, ornate furniture and pearled jewelry from the
early Tiffany's worn by Abraham Lincoln's wife - with lots in
between.
</P>
<P>
   The show culminates with a dramatic display of Frederic Edwin
Church's monumental 1859 painting, ''The Heart of the Andes,''
presented as it was originally - as a single picture in a darkened
room. It is shown in a reconstruction of the original elaborate,
freestanding wooden frame.
</P>
<P>
   The work was displayed at a fair in New York in 1864, which
inspired the citizens of New York to call for a city museum. That
museum became the Met itself, and the show's grand finale comes
full circle back to modern day New York.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Museum of Art: www.metmuseum.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-16-00 1347 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
