<DOCNO> APW20000916.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Severe shortage of Portuguese-speaking priests sends Archbishop on foreign recruiting tour </HEADLINE>
By WAYNE PARRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Five years ago, the Rev. Rene Lima was
serving happily as a priest in his native city of Sao Paolo,
Brazil, celebrating Mass and mingling with parishioners in one of
the world's most Roman Catholic countries.
</P>
<P>
   Then one day his bishop called him in, and told him he was being
sent elsewhere to help meet a great need. Before long, Lima was on
a plane touching down at Newark International Airport, where he ran
head-on into some staggering statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are more than 100,000 Portuguese-speaking
Catholics in northern New Jersey, there are only about 10 priests
in the archdiocese who speak the language. And with waves of
Brazilians flocking to the area, joining the well-established
community of immigrants from Portugal, the need for clergy who
speak the language is becoming more acute every day.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd love it if we had even a dozen,'' said Newark Archbishop
Theodore McCarrick, who has made reaching out to non-English
speaking parishioners a hallmark of his tenure as leader of
northern New Jersey's 1.3 million Roman Catholics. ''The reality
is, we have even less than that.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarrick recently completed a trip to Portugal, where he
engaged in the ecclesiastical version of ''Let's Make A Deal'' with
bishops there in the hope of finding some Portuguese-speaking
priests to serve in parishes in New Jersey. But he flew back
empty-handed, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not that easy,'' he said. ''Portugal is having the same
problems we're having with vocations. But I did speak to several of
the bishops in Portugal, and they feel a responsibility for the
Portuguese here.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarrick said he explored several short-term solutions with
Portuguese bishops, including lending a priest or two to the Newark
Archdiocese for a while in return for English-speaking priests who
could serve in Portuguese churches with significant
English-speaking populations. And McCarrick also hopes to send some
seminarians to Portugal to study the language and culture before
returning to Newark once they are ordained.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage has its roots in the diaspora of
Portuguese-speaking Catholics beyond their once-insular enclave in
Newark's Ironbound section, where they were quite literally penned
in by the elevated railroad tracks that defined the largely
Portuguese neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   As the economy improved, Portuguese who were renowned for their
skill as masons and restaurateurs began spreading out to areas
where there hadn't been a sizable community before. Couple that
with a recent wave of Brazilian immigrants, and you've got a quiet
explosion of Portuguese-speaking Catholics in an area with few
priests to serve them in their native tongue.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Michael Ward of St. Cecelia's R.C. Church in Kearny
spent three summers in Portugal before being ordained three years
ago. He said it's essential for parishioners, particularly new
arrivals, to be able to talk about God with someone in their own
language.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been through this myself,'' he said. ''I spent a great
deal of time in Portugal trying to learn the language, and
Portuguese not being my native tongue, it wasn't as easy to pray,''
he said. ''If we consider the Mass as a type of prayer, it's easier
to pray in your own language.''
</P>
<P>
   His parish offers a Sunday morning Mass in Portuguese that's
regularly attended by 300 to 400 people.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Lima, who was sent to St. Benedict's R.C. Church in
Newark from his native Brazil, said the church is often the first
place new immigrants go for help.
</P>
<P>
   ''When they come here, they are totally lost,'' he said. ''They
need support and guidance, and we need to welcome them. They need
housing, jobs, (work) papers, they need to learn English. Each
church tries to help as much as it can.''
</P>
<P>
   His church has held fund-raisers to help two Brazilian
parishioners who have been stricken with cancer, and occasionally
helps raise money to offset funeral and transportation expenses for
church members who have died and wanted to be buried in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Church and civic leaders agree the influx of immigrants from
Portugal has slowed dramatically, but it has been replaced with an
influx of Brazilians.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every week, at least 100 Brazilians move into this town,''
said Francisco Sampa, the president of Baua, a Brazilian civic
association in Newark. ''We are far from home, and we need
spiritual support. People miss their culture and their families,
and need support. They find it in the church.''
</P>
<P>
   The archdiocese has a much harder time allocating its resources
to serve Portuguese-speaking Catholics now because they have spread
out so much, McCarrick said.
</P>
<P>
   ''In years past, they were largely in the Ironbound section of
Newark, but now we've got sizable populations in Elizabeth,
Harrison, Kearny and many places in Union County,'' he said. ''That
makes it all the harder, because religion is so essential to the
lives of these folks.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarrick said the church will continue to look for potential
priests among its home-grown Portuguese communities, but said the
shortage probably won't ease for a few years.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm convinced that vocations will come from the community but
not right now,'' he said. ''We have three or four young men right
now in the seminary, but my concern is for the next few years.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Archdiocese of Newark: http://www.rcan.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-16-00 1349 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000916.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-assistant principal sentenced for inappropriate sex talks with boy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) - The former assistant principal of a Winslow
Township elementary school received two years' probation Friday for
making suggestive remarks to a 10-year-old boy.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Lee Tomasello could have received 18 months in prison for
each count. It was his first offense.
</P>
<P>
   Camden County Superior Court Judge Samuel D. Natal ordered
Tomasello, of Winslow, to get a job, complete 50 hours of community
service and undergo a psychological investigation of 30 days if
deemed necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Natal also barred Tomasello from contact with the victim,
seeking employment in the public sector and from involvement with
the Boy Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Tomasello had inappropriate sexual
conversations from October 1999 to last January with two male
students, then aged 10 and 12. He had been an assistant principal
at Winslow School No. 5 since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Tomasello was charged in January and freed on $5,000 bail, and
retired that month from the school district. Charges involving the
12-year-old were later dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   At the sentencing hearing, no one spoke on behalf of Tomasello,
who had pleaded guilty as part of an agreement with the prosecutor.
Several letters commending his character, however, were submitted
to the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Guardians for the now 11-year-old boy asked Natal to impose the
maximum sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ''They feel shame, emptiness and mistrust,'' one guardian said.
''These children were entrusted to Tomasello. To prey on a child is
cruel.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomasello and his lawyer declined comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
