<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Standards for judges in some courts same as frontier days  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER JORDAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   COXSACKIE, N.Y. (AP) - With handwritten ''Check with the officer
on arrival'' signs tacked to rafters, and a tin of chocolates
kisses on a table, Judge Richard Roberg's courtroom looks like a
piece of America's past.
</P>
<P>
   What Roberg had to do to become a town judge, or rather what he
didn't do, is also something from another time. Roberg was a
longtime 10th grade math teacher before donning a black robe 20
years ago. Along with 1,750 other town and village judges in the
state, he never went to law school before getting the power to put
people in jail for up to a year, to order dogs killed and to assess
fines.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing judges to serve without formal legal training dates
back to frontier days, when the country was young and lawyers
scarce. Yet because hiring lawyers is expensive, and in some rural
spots still impossible, and since many believe education does not
necessarily ensure justice, little has changed. And little is
expected to any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ''Twenty-five years ago, when a lot of court reforms were being
pushed around the country ... legally trained judges became far
more the norm,'' said Kenneth Pankey, of the National Center for
State Courts in Virginia. ''There are so few states where now this
is an issue at all.''
</P>
<P>
   New York, along with Texas, has the greatest number of judges
not professionally trained as lawyers. Other states with nonlawyer
judges include Mississippi, Arizona, South Carolina, Georgia and
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have town and village justices sitting in their eighties,''
said Gerald Stern, of the state Commission on Judicial Conduct.
''Of those sitting for the longest time, many did not have any
full-time education. Some may have sixth- or eighth-grade education
and some have high school education. A small percentage have
college degrees.''
</P>
<P>
   The state constitution requires that higher court judges, from
the Court of Appeals down to surrogate and family courts, must be
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Town and village judges undergo a one-week training before
beginning work and once a year after that. The standards for the
town and village judges, almost all of whom are elected, are not so
different for other, seemingly less powerful, jobs. To become a
technician that waxes unwanted hair off eyebrows, for example, New
York requires 75 hours of classes.
</P>
<P>
   Even to a former educator like Roberg, though, the lack of
educational standards is OK. He believes Republicans chose him to
run because he was well-regarded as a teacher. And, frankly,
because no lawyer would accept the $12,000 he earns for the
part-time job annually.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have doubts,'' Roberg said about being a judge without a
law degree. ''I thought law was quite intrinsic and complicated and
it can be. But you know what? Mostly it's good common sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberg's demeanor and the homey setting clearly make people less
nervous when they visit for the first time his courtroom in
Coxsackie, 21 miles south of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   The old storefront court is in the center of the one-block
business district on Main Street. Next door is a century-old
restaurant that was once a watering hold for shipmen taking a break
from transporting ice and produce on the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent court session, a widow with a thick Italian accent
blew the judge a smooch after a loan dispute was settled. A young
West Point cadet asked the judge to advise her on what to plead to
a Thruway speeding ticket.
</P>
<P>
   In all his years on the bench, Roberg only ordered one dog
destroyed, because it was wild. ''That hurt,'' he said. ''I'll
never forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   There are horror stories about nonlawyers making decisions that
appeared to be based on anything but common sense. Like in the case
of Thomas R. Buckley, a retired phone worker who had been a judge
in Dannemora since 1987 until his career was ended this year by the
Commission on Judicial Conduct.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's ruling cited Buckley for, without a hearing and
no witnesses other than himself, ordering the destruction of his
neighbor's 12-year-old beagle because he saw it running loose.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers' shortcomings can certainly be just as egregious. J.
Kevin Mulroy, a lawyer who served as a judge in Onondaga County for
13 years, was ousted this year for using racist remarks and
profanity on the bench and in social settings.
</P>
<P>
   Law degree aside, Roberg too is aghast at the lack of
professionalism some counterparts show. He shakes his head in
disbelief when asked what he thinks about judges who hold court in
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ''That doesn't happen does it?'' he asked, before allowing, ''At
least get an office in a fire company or something, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   The Office of Court Administration says less than one percent of
judges hold court in their homes and suggests it's a fading
phenomenon. Yet home meetings are not exclusive to judges on the
edge of retirement. Some open doors to their homes as a sort of
social service.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent night, 30-year-old Mendin Judge June Patterson had
the police bring a 16-year-old drug addict to her home in handcuffs
- for brownies, milk and encouragement to get treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Which proves the point of Paul Biderman, of the National
Association of Judicial Educators, who says nonlawyer justices tend
to be more creative about problem solving than their trained
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   And, Biderman added, ''the stakes are not so high,'' in the
cases town and village courts handle. In these lower level courts,
judges rule in misdemeanors. For most felony cases, they arraign
suspects and turn the cases over to higher courts.
</P>
<P>
   Some statistics offer little proof that lawyers are necessarily
better judges. Last year, .04 percent of nonlawyer village or town
judges were disciplined in the state. Among lawyer judges, 1
percent were disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers prove nothing, said Laurie Shanks, a professor at
Albany Law School. ''If you have one town justice and lawyers who
have to practice before the judge over and over again, are they
going to run the risk of going to the Commission?''
</P>
<P>
   Shanks said that the acceptance of nonlawyer justices is bound
to be challenged again, as it was 24 years ago, when lawyers in
Kentucky, New York, and Utah were trying to get verdicts overturned
based on the judges' familiarity with the law.
</P>
<P>
   The American Judicature Society said at the time the lay-judge
system ''violates the due process clause of the Fourteenth
Amendment to the United States Constitution and undermines the
effective administration of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, though, in the Kentucky case, the U.S. Supreme Court
ruled 6-2 that nonlawyer judges could serve over criminal trials
when defendants can appeal for a second trial before a judge who is
a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, though, New York's Office of Court
Administration says there have been no challenges to allowing
non-lawyer judges. When New York's Chief Judge Judith Kaye and Gov.
George Pataki proposed court reforms this year, there was no
mention of requiring law degrees for town and village courts.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it's as if everyone accepts what Kentucky's Court of
Appeals declared in the aforementioned case: ''We fully appreciate
the absurdity of having a lawsuit - any lawsuit - presided over in
this day and age by a person without legal training or experience.
Nevertheless ... the federal Constitution does not deny the people
the right to have it that way if they so desire.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-16-00 1404 </TRAILER>
