<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton camp calls Lazio bully; he says he's a fighter  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - In aggressively going after Hillary Rodham
Clinton during the first debate of their Senate campaign,
Republican Rick Lazio risked a possible backlash the first lady's
campaign has been encouraging ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The visually defining moment came at the very end of the
one-hour debate Wednesday night when Lazio walked to Clinton's
podium, waving his pledge to ban soft money from the campaign under
her nose and demanding her signature. She demurred.
</P>
<P>
   When he crossed the stage, he crossed the line, according to the
Clinton camp.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton campaign spokesman, Howard Wolfson, said the congressman
from Long Island appeared ''menacing'' at that moment.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's not a nice guy,'' Wolfson told cable television's New
York 1. ''He looked senatorial in the tradition of Bobby Knight,''
the fired Indiana University basketball coach.
</P>
<P>
   Since the debate there has been much talk about the danger men
face attacking women in politics and the fine line to be walked
when doing so.
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio camp insists any backlash on that front is
''mythical'' and exists largely in the minds of members of the
media.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can go too far, but he didn't,'' said Mike Murphy, Lazio's
chief campaign strategist. ''He didn't make any real personal
attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They lost the debate. Their campaign is in trouble and they
know it,'' Murphy added. ''Their candidate did not perform and so
they're inventing this canard to try to distract everybody from the
defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   A poll of 274 registered voters who watched the debate,
conducted for the New York Daily News and WCBS-TV by Blum &AMP; Weprin
Associates, gave the edge to Clinton, 49 percent to 36 percent,
when it came to who had done a ''better job'' in the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the debate, independent polls had shown that while
Clinton was making some gains among white women voters - a key bloc
for her and one where she had been trailing - Lazio was still doing
well among them.
</P>
<P>
   The morning after the debate, Lazio and his aides were defending
the congressman's aggressive style. They were also being asked
about the wisdom of attacking Clinton for blaming the ''vast
right-wing conspiracy'' during the Monica Lewinsky scandal. Polling
then had shown the first lady's standing highest when she was
viewed as a victim.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll leave that for strategists,'' Lazio said Thursday when
asked about such concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ''This isn't high tea. It's the Senate race in New York,'' Lazio
spokesman Dan McLagan said.
</P>
<P>
   That was a theme pushed by Lazio as well.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a race for the Senate, people expect plain talk,'' the
congressman said Thursday before leaving Buffalo, appearing pleased
with himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you go to the Senate, you've to be prepared to fight for
New York,'' he added during his next campaign stop at a charter
school in Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in Oswego County, Lazio told supporters that viewers of
the debate ''found out something else about New Yorkers - we don't
back down from a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he was at a farm near Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the Senate, nobody's going to care if you're a man or a
woman,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to the debate from pundits and voters has varied.
</P>
<P>
   New York Times columnist Gail Collins wrote that while Lazio
''was supposed to be the 'likable' candidate'' he ''morphed into a
political predator. Darth Vader with dimples ... (''Survivor'' show
winner) Richard Hatch with clothes on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post's David Broder came away from the debate
believing ''the 'stature gap' between Hillary Rodham Clinton and
her challenger, Rep. Rick Lazio, is smaller than many Democrats
would wish.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan McCormack, an undecided Democrat from Rochester told the
Buffalo News that she came away from the debate still undecided,
but feeling Lazio was ''too rough.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody who would like to slap her, raise your hand,'' said
Arthur Deruve of Yonkers as he watched the debate at the Sons of
Italy Lodge in White Plains.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Marc Humbert has covered New York politics for The Associated
Press for more than 20 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-16-00 1409 </TRAILER>
