<HEADLINE> Milosevic Challenger: Vote Is Fixed  </HEADLINE>
By KATARINA KRATOVAC
<TEXT>
<P>
   NOVI SAD, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Slobodan Milosevic's main challenger
warned Saturday the Yugoslav president will use ''thugs and liars''
to rig this month's presidential election. The warning came as the
government continued its crackdown on opposition supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a rally here in the country's main northern city,
Vojislav Kostunica told about 20,000 supporters that Milosevic's
''thugs and liars are known for stealing.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They have stolen years of our lives,'' said Kostunica, who is
leading Milosevic in opinion polls before the Sept. 24 balloting.
''And now they are preparing the theft of the century,'' to secure
victory for the Yugoslav president.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica was referring to widespread fears that Milosevic, who
has been indicted by the international tribunal in The Hague for
war crimes, could resort to fraud and violence to stay in power.
</P>
<P>
   ''But we will cast more votes than they can steal,'' Kostunica
said. The crowd responded by cheering ''He's finished,'' referring
to Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   With the crucial election drawing near, police continued their
crackdown on Milosevic's opponents. Three members of the popular,
anti-Milosevic student group, Otpor, were arrested Saturday in
Belgrade for putting up posters urging people to vote against the
autocratic ruler.
</P>
<P>
   Two more Otpor activists were arrested Saturday in the northern
town of Subotica near the border with Hungary but were released,
the group's central office said.
</P>
<P>
   A leading human rights group in Serbia, the Humanitarian Law
Fund, also said police beat two Otpor members Friday for
distributing leaflets and stickers calling for resistance to
Milosevic's regime.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, 22 opposition activists were arrested in various
towns across the country but were eventually released. Police
raided at least two offices of nongovernment groups, also seizing
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica is backed by an alliance of 18 opposition parties. He
is considered the strongest of the three major candidates running
against Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Saturday, Kostunica told supporters in the northern town
of Sombor that he was calling not for revolution ''but democracy''
in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most of all we need a normal life in a normal country ... a
government that will put an end to the sanctions imposed by the
international community and assure that people can lead decent,
peaceful lives,'' Kostunica said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, 22 opposition activists were arrested in various
towns. Police raided at least two offices of nongovernment groups,
seizing computers and holding the detainees who were released after
hours-long questioning.
</P>
</TEXT>
