<BODY>
<HEADLINE> End to Austria Sanctions Analyzed  </HEADLINE>
By DEBORAH SEWARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- With the diplomatic sanctions that failed to keep
the far right from power in Austria now lifted, Europeans are
pondering the lessons of the punishment and wondering if the bitter
experience could poison relations among European Union members.
</P>
<P>
   Two key questions whirled around European capitals after
Wednesday's decision to end Austria's diplomatic isolation: Was
anything of value learned? And was the discord the sanctions caused
worth it?
</P>
<P>
   Only one thing seemed sure at week's end: The European Union
didn't look set to discipline one of its members again soon.
</P>
<P>
   Romano Prodi, chairman of the European Commission -- the EU's
executive body -- told the Austrian magazine Format that while the
inclusion of a radical party in government was ''very irritating,''
the European Union would have to live with it.
</P>
<P>
   ''That won't happen again,'' Prodi said of the sanctions. ''A
bigger Europe will often have problems, but we will have to respect
the results of those elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Excerpts of the interview, which was to appear in Monday's
issue, were distributed Saturday by the Austria Press Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The EU took the unprecedented act of imposing sanctions on
Austria in February, after Chancellor Wolfgang Schuessel decided to
include members of the far-right Freedom Party in a coalition
government with his Austrian People's Party. Freedom Party leader
Joerg Haider has raised alarm in Europe for past statements
sympathetic to aspects of the Nazi regime, as well as for his
party's strong anti-immigrant rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   A report commissioned by the EU released Tuesday concluded that
the sanctions, which ranged from freezing bilateral relations
between Austria and its 14 EU partners to boycotts of school trips,
were counterproductive and should be halted. A day later, France,
which now holds the EU presidency, announced they were lifted.
</P>
<P>
   ''Austria's position is very unpleasant. It will take years,
possibly a decade, to repair the damage,'' said Arnold Suppan, a
history professor at the University of Vienna. ''The sanctions have
been lifted, but they are still having an effect.''
</P>
<P>
   In at least two respects, the sanctions clearly backfired. They
did not force Schuessel to abandon the Freedom Party -- which
remains part of the governing coalition -- and, according to the EU
report, they reinforced nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   ''The EU partners did not obtain change, so it's a relative
failure,'' said Phillipe Moreau Defarges, a senior fellow at the
French Institute for International Relations.
</P>
<P>
   For smaller EU nations, the sanctions deepened their worst fears
of being dominated by the larger ones, of interference in their own
democratic affairs. In Denmark, where a referendum is to be held
Sept. 28 on whether to accept the single European currency, the
sanctions issue has hurt support, according to a recent poll.
</P>
<P>
   ''For small countries, this was chilling, and I don't think they
will act in such a panicky way in the future,'' Suppan said.
</P>
<P>
   For bigger countries, the sanctions showed the risk of taking
the moral high ground and interfering in the politics of a member
nation. For French President Jacques Chirac, one of the strongest
supporters of the measures, the EU report was a humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The participation of an extremist and xenophobic party in a
European government is abnormal in the Europe of today,'' Chirac
said Friday in his first public comment after the sanctions ended.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is out of the question to trivialize an ideology that has
not broken with a disastrous past,'' Chirac said, reaffirming the
EU's intention to keep a close watch on Austria's political
development.
</P>
<P>
   Influential French dailies on the left and the right were
unsparing in their criticism. The leftist Liberation called the
sanctions a ''bitter pill'' for Chirac.
</P>
<P>
   ''The European Union cannot punish one of its members without
blocking its own work,'' Le Figaro said.
</P>
<P>
   In Vienna, Haider, crowing, called the sanctions a ''complete
flop,'' and heaped scorn on Chirac.
</P>
<P>
   For history professor Tony Judt, director of the Remarque
Institute at New York University and a keen observer of Austria,
the sanctions had an unintended side effect.
</P>
<P>
   The measures showed just how many people outside of Austria,
where Haider long has been a familiar part of the political
landscape, are put off by him, Judt said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It certainly woke up Austrian politicians and intellectuals
community in a big way,'' Judt said.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from that, Judt added, the sanctions were a ''gross
error.''
</P>
<P>
   During the next three months, France has the difficult job of
trying to get the EU to adopt institutional reforms as it prepares
to expand, and the sanctions could come back to haunt the EU.
</P>
<P>
   ''The crisis is not over,'' Moreau Defarges said. ''There is a
malaise. ... If Austria is too arrogant, the crisis is going to
start again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-16-00 1513 </TRAILER>
