<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Warmer Ties With India  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM C. MANN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said Saturday he would work
for closer U.S. ties with India in hopes of stemming a ''dangerous
tide of proliferation of dangerous weapons'' in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Standing feet away from a newly dedicated statue of Mohandas K.
Gandhi, the Indian independence leader and advocate of nonviolence,
Clinton spoke of ''a whole new era of partnership between India and
the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   He then addressed the nuclear saber-rattling by India and
neighboring Pakistan, and the need to defuse tensions.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope we'll both be able to help to turn back what could
otherwise be a dangerous tide of proliferation of dangerous weapons
-- not just nuclear warheads on missiles, either, (but) chemical
weapons, biological weapons. I hope we'll be able to turn that
back.
</P>
<P>
   ''And I hope some day that there will be some constructive role
we could play as a partner in working with India and others to
bring peace on the subcontinent.''
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton at his side, Atal Bihari Vajpayee, India's ailing
prime minister, whose official visit to Washington ends with a
White House dinner Sunday, dedicated the almost 9-foot-tall Gandhi
statue in a canopy of trees across from the Indian Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   The bronze statue depicts Gandhi, assassinated by a Hindu
fanatic in 1948, in a classic pose, dressed in peasant's clothes
and striding with the aid of a staff.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee, 75, who has chronic pain in his left knee from
osteoarthritis, which erodes the cartilage around the knee, walked
in small steps, sometimes with Clinton's hand under Vajpayee's arm
or supporting his back.
</P>
<P>
   During the Cold War, India was a founder of the Nonaligned
Nations Movement, conceived as a third course between capitalism
and communism. In practice, India, the world's second most populous
country after China, appeared to side more often with the Soviet
Union than with the other superpower.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the officially neutral United States seemed
often to favor openly India's adversary Pakistan, especially in the
1971 war that dissected Pakistan and created Bangladesh from its
eastern half.
</P>
<P>
   Current problems between the two focus on Vajpayee's return to
nuclear testing in May 1998. The tests, India's first since 1974,
led to retaliatory tests by Pakistan and to Clinton's assessment
this year that the subcontinent is perhaps the world's ''most
dangerous place.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither country has signed the international Comprehensive
Test-Ban Treaty. The United States, which has signed but not
ratified it, has sanctions in place against India for not signing.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was clearly pleased Saturday with the rapport he has
found with Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
   The visit ''sort of rounds out our efforts to take a different
turn in our relationships, to deepen and broaden them,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope that this change in partnership goes beyond my service
(as president), into a whole new era of partnership between India
and the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a natural fit, he said. ''There is probably no country
outside India that has been more enriched by Indians than the
United States,'' he said. ''So that's another reason I think it's
important we continue to go forward together.''
</P>
<P>
   Indian-Americans contributed toward the cost of the Mahatma
Gandhi Memorial, which was built by the Indian government in
collaboration with the U.S. government and the National Park
Service.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: State Department background on India:
http://www.state.gov/www/regions/sa/index.html
</P>
<P>
   Embassy of India: http://www.indianembassy.org
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister's Office of India: http://pmindia.nic.in
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
