<HEADLINE> Haider Makes Surprise Visit to Italy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRIESTE, Italy (AP) -- Far-right Austrian politician Joerg Haider
made a surprise appearance Saturday at a local ceremony across the
border in Italy -- his first known one since Italy asked Austria to
do what it could to keep him away.
</P>
<P>
   ''What an ugly surprise,'' fumed the vice mayor of Trieste,
Roberto Damiani, one of the officials taking part -- by invitation --
in the ceremony on the outskirts of the northern city of Trieste.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to make a political issue of it, but it's just
bad manners,'' Damiani said.
</P>
<P>
   Applause mixed with catcalls greeted Haider when he appeared at
an anniversary ceremony for a thoroughfare linking Trieste and
Vienna. The road opened 170 years ago, when that part of Italy was
under Austrian rule.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third known trip to northern Italy in three months by
Haider, who angered some Italian officials over the summer by
proposing a ''super-region'' between northern Italian provinces and
the Austrian province of Carinthia. Haider is governor of
Carinthia.
</P>
<P>
   Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini wrote his Austrian
counterpart on July 22 to ask Austria to take ''all the possible
measures to avoid'' more protest-provoking cross-border trips by
Haider.
</P>
<P>
   The letter came in the middle of what was Haider's second trip
to northern Italy that month.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a private citizen and I can go where I wish,'' Haider was
quoted as telling Italian journalists asking his itinerary for the
day Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Haider unexpectedly took the place of another Carinthian
official invited to the ceremony, Italian media said.
</P>
<P>
   When Haider rose at one point, apparently to make some remarks,
the center-left Trieste vice mayor reportedly asked him to keep his
seat.
</P>
<P>
   Haider told local reporters that relations between Austria and
northern Italy had improved since he started making his trips, and
said cooperation should move faster now that the European Union has
lifted sanctions against his country.
</P>
<P>
   He called the lifting of the sanctions after seven months ''a
great victory by Austrian democracy against illegal pressure from
outside.''
</P>
<P>
   He also told Italian reporters he was ''very hopeful'' the
center-right would win in their country's next national elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
