<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mediator in Buffalo teachers' dispute labeled no longer useful  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - A state mediator who was taken on a central
role in the Buffalo teachers' pay dispute has ''outlived his
usefulness'' over the last 10 months and become too closely tied to
their union, the school board president asserts.
</P>
<P>
   Under orders by a judge, striking teachers returned to work
without a contract Friday and promised to stay there until a
proposal is released Tuesday by mediator Alan Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman is being assisted by the state Public Employment
Relations Board, which determined last December that the union and
the district were at an impasse that required state intervention.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo Teachers Federation's 3,700 teachers walked out for
two days earlier this month and unexpectedly resumed the strike
Thursday, canceling classes for 47,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Buchanan, president of the Buffalo Board of Education,
thinks Kaufman can no longer can be counted on to help settle the
dispute - a view echoed by fellow board members. Kaufman had a role
in organizing contract settlements in 1994 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has outlived his usefulness,'' Buchanan said. ''Ten months
to mediate a dispute that has ended up in two strikes, and now
trying to assert himself, seems to me to be a day late and a dollar
short. He has been immersed in it too long.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman did not return telephone messages seeking his comment,
but the union denied that it had any special relationship with him
or the Public Employment Relations Board.
</P>
<P>
   That board's job, said teachers' union president Phil Rumore,
has been ''to beat up on us a lot. They can come into us, they have
threatened, they are using every tactic they can.'' At the same
time, the board has calmed proceedings and ''the strike has been
delayed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice Kevin Dillon sharply criticized
Thursday's sudden walkout and solidified a temporary order against
the walkout.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said the district's latest offer Wednesday contained
annual hikes of 2.5 to 3.5 percent for the next three years. The
teachers want slightly higher raises, he said. The increases would
be on top of automatic 2 percent annual raises, district officials
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
