<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Kan. Lottery Worker Accused  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN HANNA
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) -- A former lottery administrator is accused of
using his access to the agency's computers to steal tens of
thousands of dollars from the Kansas Lottery through dozens of
small cash payments.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Lee Knowlton, 55, was charged Friday with 268 criminal
counts involving felony computer crime, theft and official
misconduct. He was the lottery's information resource manager from
1992 until March, when he resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Karla Stovall accused Knowlton of altering
lottery tickets and computer files so he could present winning
tickets to retailers and claim cash prizes that were small enough
not to be too suspicious but that brought him $62,000 over 18
months, ending in March.
</P>
<P>
   He is accused only of creating additional winning tickets for
himself, not changing other players' tickets, and his actions did
not alter the outcome of any drawings, Stovall said.
</P>
<P>
   Knowlton's attorney, William Rork, did not return a telephone
message from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Knowlton said in Friday editions of The Topeka Capital-Journal
that he had no comment. ''I think you will hear a lot more about
this in the near future. There is a lot more to this than meets the
eye,'' he told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Since Knowlton resigned, the lottery has changed its operations
so no one person has unrestricted access to its main computer and
every keystroke is now monitored, said Ed Van Petten, the lottery's
deputy director. He said no other lottery employees are under
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Kansas Lottery: http://www.kslottery.com/
</P>
</TEXT>
