<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, Sept. 16, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Hurricane Watch in Florida
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Florida Gov. Jeb Bush activated emergency response teams
today as Tropical Storm Gordon threatened to become a hurricane and strike
Florida's Gulf Coast. Up to 5 inches of rain is possible by tomorrow in the Keys
and much of South Florida, officials said. The storm already had poured up to 10
inches of rain on western Cuba early in the day. Storm watches and warnings were
posted along much of Florida's Gulf Coast, and several counties recommended
voluntary evacuations of barrier islands and coastal or low lying areas.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Urges Warmer Ties With India
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said today he would work for closer U.S.
ties with India in hopes of stemming a ''dangerous tide of proliferation of
dangerous weapons'' in South Asia. Standing feet away from a newly dedicated
statue of Mohandas K. Gandhi, the Indian independence leader and advocate of
nonviolence, Clinton spoke of ''a whole new era of partnership between India and
the United States.'' He then addressed the nuclear saber-rattling by India and
neighboring Pakistan, and the need to defuse tensions.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Violence Escalates at Colombia Universities
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MONTERIA, Colombia (AP) -- Escalating campus violence, including the
assassinations of several professors, is turning Colombia's universities into
battlegrounds. The latest victim was Hugo Iguaran, an outspoken professor killed
Sept. 10 during a meeting at the home of the rector of the University of
Cordoba, located in this northern city. In just over a year, five professors in
Colombia have been killed and others have been attacked or kidnapped. ''There is
a climate here of fear, of anxiety, of distrust,'' said industrial science
professor Hery Castillo, president of the University of Cordoba teachers'
association.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Wildfire Rages in Colorado
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOULDER, Colo. (AP) -- Flames leapt from tree to tree and shot high into the
air today as a wildfire raged through almost 500 acres west of the city,
prompting authorities to call for the evacuation of 200 mountain homes. A plume
of smoke thousands of feet high was visible from Fort Collins, nearly 50 miles
away. Lt. Joe Gang, spokesman for the Boulder County Sheriff's Office, issued an
urgent plea for more help, saying the 100 firefighters struggling to extinguish
the blaze had been slowed by the area's rough terrain.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Polls: Gore Leads Industrial States
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore has opened leads in three of the big industrial
states in America's heartland and erased George W. Bush's advantage in a fourth,
according to new polls offering fresh evidence of the Democrat's surge in states
central to the presidential race. In the surveys released today by a Michigan
pollster, the vice president had an edge in Michigan, a state that has been a
dead heat for weeks; had wide leads in Pennsylvania and Illinois, supporting
earlier polls; and had pulled into a tie in Ohio, the Midwestern state that most
favors GOP presidential candidates.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Wife of IOC President Dies
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- Maria Teresa Salisachs-Rowe, the wife of International
Olympic Committee president Juan Antonio Samaranch, died today in Barcelona
after a long illness, according to reports. She was 67. The state news agency
Efe cited sources close to the family. A friend who answered the phone at the
family home in Barcelona said Samaranch's wife died today but didn't provide
further details. Samaranch left the Sydney Olympics this morning, just hours
after the opening ceremony, to be with his wife. Efe said he hadn't arrived in
Barcelona when his wife died.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Men's Soccer Opens With Ties
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) -- The U.S. men have miscued, mistimed and just
plain missed dozens of goal chances as they've opened the Olympic soccer
tournament with ties against Cameroon and the Czech Republic. But coach Clive
Charles says the law of averages is on their side. ''No, I'm not concerned,''
Charles said after strikers Conor Casey and Josh Wolff wasted at least four
genuine scoring opportunities in Saturday's 1-1 tie against Cameroon at
Canberra. Going into the last preliminary round, the United States faces a
must-win game against Kuwait in Melbourne on Tuesday, while Cameroon takes on
the winless Czech Republic.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Notre Dame Beats Purdue, 23-21
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) -- Nick Setta kicked a 38-yard field goal as time
expired to give No. 21 Notre Dame a 23-21 victory over mistake-prone Purdue
today. Shane Walton returned an interception 60 yards for a touchdown as the
Irish (2-1) scored 17 points off Purdue mistakes to send the Boilermakers to
their 12th straight loss at Notre Dame. The Boilermakers (2-1) also were hurt by
a blocked punt that set up a Notre Dame touchdown and a failed fake punt that
led to an Irish field goal.
AP NewsBrief by GRETCHEN SCHWARTZ 
</P>
