<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani joins Lazio, while Clinton stumps in suburbs  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton got friendly with her
voting neighbors in Chappaqua on Saturday, while her rival Rick
Lazio pounded the Manhattan pavement with two brash New Yorkers at
his side: Yankees owner George Steinbrenner and Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Barely a day after his prostate cancer treatment, the Republican
mayor walked in the annual German-American Steuben Parade up Fifth
Avenue on a crisp September day.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a cap inscribed ''Mount Sinai'' - the hospital where he
underwent the procedure Friday - Giuliani said the doctors there
''did it in such a skillful way that I'm able to march.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees' owner Steinbrenner, the parade's grand marshall, joined
the mayor for a news conference at Park Avenue and 86th Street, the
end of the parade route that started at 63rd Street and Fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Before they stepped off at noon, accompanied by Judith Nathan,
the woman Giuliani calls his ''very good friend,'' the mayor
received hugs from both Lazio and Steinbrenner. ''You're amazing!''
Lazio whispered in Giuliani's ear.
</P>
<P>
   In the crowd lining Fifth Avenue, one man wore a pro-Lazio cap
that said, ''Made in New York,'' a dig at Clinton's carpetbagger
status. And a group of spectators held a long banner that read:
''VIP Hillary. Vicious, insufferable phony.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani walked over to them and said, ''Hold it up higher!''
</P>
<P>
   Observing his fellow Republican, Lazio said the mayor was an
inspiration to ''cancer survivors around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor had radioactive seeds implanted in his cancerous
prostate gland Friday, and held a news conference five hours later.
Doctors at Mount Sinai said the treatment went ''perfectly'' and
called the mayor' prognosis ''excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Saturday, Lazio marched in the Westchester County
volunteer firefighters parade in Tarrytown. Along with state Sen.
Nicholas Spano and Tarrytown Mayor Paul Janos, Lazio brought up the
read of the parade, marching in front of his campaign bus, ''The
Mainstream Express,'' which blasted rock music.
</P>
<P>
   In the Westchester community of Chappaqua, where Clinton now
lives, she appeared at the 17th Annual Community Day hosted by the
Chappaqua Rotary Club at the railroad station.
</P>
<P>
   She strolled past stands that offered everything from blood
pressure screenings to hot dogs, Girl Scout cupcakes and campaign
tables for Gore-Lieberman, as well as Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton greeted volunteers at the table of the Democratic
presidential ticket, drawing hundreds of people. She also met
singer-actress Vanessa Williams, a native of nearby Millwood.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was asked to comment on a Daily News story Saturday
about the American Conservative Union, which had rejected a request
to refrain from personally criticizing her. She said the group
''has been supporting Rick Lazio for months, and they have proudly
said they sent out something like seven million letters and books
on his behalf. And so I think it's a clear indication that there
isn't any serious effort being taken to rein in those so-called
independent expenditure groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the same issue earlier in the day, Lazio said: ''I'm
prepared to not just call on all outside groups, but if anybody was
to resist our call, I'm prepared to repudiate the ads - if she's
willing to do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, accused by her opponent of being unfamiliar with
New York, also sang the praises of the town she's known since last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't know about Chappaqua before we found the house
here,'' she said. ''But now, everywhere I go there are people who
have relatives or friends or connections with Chappaqua. So there
is an extensive - I don't know what the word is,'' she said,
turning to town supervisor Marion Sinik. ''Marion, what is it,
Chappaquidians? Chappa-what? Chappaquidians? What do we call
ourselves?''
</P>
<P>
   Sinik replied: ''Residents of Chappaqua.''
</P>
<P>
   At the near-empty Republican table, the chairman of the town
Republican Party, Ed O'Keefe, said Clinton's move to Chappaqua
''has been a boon to local Republicans. We used to have three
people on the town committee. Now we have 30.''
</P>
</TEXT>
