<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tabloid, Giffords Fight Over Story  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Tabloid lawyers have asked a judge
to throw out a libel lawsuit filed by Kathie Lee and Frank Gifford,
saying a story depicting the couple's 9-year-old son as a bratty
monster didn't harm the boy.
</P>
<P>
   But the Giffords' lawyer said the National Examiner article
claiming Cody spit out food in a restaurant, behaved badly on a TV
movie set and colored on a pair of pants in a clothing store was
fabricated.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's made up and it's defamatory,'' Deborah Drooz said after a
Friday court hearing. ''They hurt a 9-year-old kid.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giffords sued the Boca Raton-based tabloid after the
February story appeared.
</P>
<P>
   National Examiner lawyer Gerson A. Zweifach told Judge Timothy
McCarthy on Friday that accounts of Cody's behavior don't meet
defamatory law standards. The boy would have had to suffer ridicule
or disgrace as a result of the story.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think you subject one to ridicule or disgrace for
(saying he) spit out squid,'' Zweifach said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge didn't indicate when he would issue a decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-16-00 1732 </TRAILER>
