<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sandy Hook, Raritan Bay cleanup ends, clam ban remains after fuel leak </HEADLINE>
By WAYNE PARRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLETOWN TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) - Cleanup crews finished work
Saturday in Sandy Hook Bay, two days after a Navy ship spilled
30,000 gallons of diesel fuel into the water.
</P>
<P>
   But a ban on harvesting shellfish in the area remained in
effect.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Environmental Protection imposed the ban
Friday morning. It was expected to remain in effect until at least
Tuesday. DEP officials will meet Monday to discuss when it will be
safe to re-open the clam beds, spokeswoman Loretta O'Donnell said.
</P>
<P>
   A tugboat helping guide the USS Detroit, a Navy supply ship,
toward the pier at the Earle Naval Weapons Station in the Leonard
section of Middletown collided with the 58,000-ton ship Thursday
afternoon, ripping a 4-foot-by-4-inch hole in its side.
</P>
<P>
   That allowed 30,000 gallons of No. 2 diesel fuel to spill into
the bay, prompting a cleanup involving vessels from the Navy, the
U.S. Coast Guard and private companies.
</P>
<P>
   The effort was completed at about 3 p.m. Saturday, said Earle
Commander Chuck Caudill.
</P>
<P>
   ''We completed what we call a tug wash, where we sprayed water
under the pier, and it came out clear,'' he said. ''We're starting
to collect the booms because this is now considered cleaned up. As
of now, there is no sheen anywhere in the bay.''
</P>
<P>
   Earle officials had no estimate on how much of the fuel was
recovered from the water using absorbent booms and ''skimmer''
ships that scrape it from the water's surface. But Andrew Willner,
the baykeeper for New York and New Jersey, said such cleanups
typically remove only about 15 percent of spilled fuel from the
water.
</P>
<P>
   A storm that rolled through the region early Friday morning
wrecked much of the containment booms that cleanup ships had placed
around the slick, allowing it to spread. Winds and high waves from
the storm dissipated most of the 4-mile-long slick on Friday, and
there were no reports of fuel washing up on any New Jersey beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists fear the toxic effects of the fuel on marine
life and migratory shore birds, but there were no reports of any
animals dying as a result of the spill.
</P>
<P>
   The clamming ban forced the closure Friday and Saturday of a
depuration plant in nearby Highlands, where clams harvested from
the Sandy Hook and Raritan bays are processed to remove
contaminants.
</P>
<P>
   The 23,000 acres of shellfish beds in northern Monmouth County
produce almost 40 million clams a year, or about one out of every
four sold in New Jersey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-16-00 1742 </TRAILER>
