<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Jersey class-action lawsuit filed against Ford, Firestone  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) - A class-action lawsuit has been filed
against Ford Motor Co. and the maker of Bridgestone/Firestone tires
on behalf of New Jersey customers, accusing the companies of
knowingly marketing defective and potentially dangerous tires and
in some cases refusing requests to have them replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Filed Friday in Superior Court in Bergen County, the lawsuit
charges that the automaker and the tire manufacturer violated the
state consumer fraud act by marketing unsafe tires.
</P>
<P>
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration has said it
is investigating 88 deaths and more than 250 injuries over the past
decade involving Firestone tires. A recall of 6.5 million ATX,
ATX-II and Wilderness AT tires was announced Aug. 9, mostly on Ford
Explorers.
</P>
<P>
   The NHTSA in May began investigating accidents in which
Firestone tires suddenly lost their tread or suffered blowouts.
Many cases involved Ford Explorers rolling over.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed on behalf of New Jersey residents who
bought or leased Explorers, Lincoln Mountaineers or other Ford
vehicles that came equipped with the tires specified in the recall.
</P>
<P>
   No dollar amount was specified in the New Jersey action, but it
seeks recovery of out-of-pocket replacement costs and related
expenses stemming from the use of the vehicles and other
inconveniences.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, one of several dozen similar actions brought in
state and federal courts around the country, also seeks to penalize
the companies under New Jersey law and require the return of
profits.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Ford: http://www.ford.com/
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone/Firestone: http://www.firestone.com
</P>
<P>
   National Highway Traffic Safety Administration:
http://www.nhtsa.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
