<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jenoff says rabbi also tried to have witness slain  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) - A private investigator who says Rabbi Fred
Neulander hired him to kill Neulander's wife also claims the rabbi
tried to have a witness slain.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Jenoff has admitted hitting Carol Neulander in the back
of the head with a metal pipe in her Cherry Hill home. He pleaded
guilty to aggravated manslaughter and agreed to testify against
Neulander in the Nov. 1, 1994, killing.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities claim the rabbi wanted his wife of 29 years dead so
he could continue an affair with Philadelphia radio personality
Elaine Soncini. Neulander allegedly believed a divorce would
jeopardize his position as senior rabbi at a synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   The Courier-Post of Cherry Hill reported in Saturday's editions
that Jenoff told authorities that Neulander suggested using a stun
gun against Pepe Levin, a Pennsauken businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander allegedly made the request after he found out Levin
had testified against him before a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony, Levin said Neulander had asked if he knew
anyone willing to kill Neulander's wife, the Courier-Post reported.
Levin also said the rabbi had expressed a desire to go home one
night and find his wife dead on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said to me that Pepe had, uh, a bad heart or had heart
attacks, that if the gun was placed on his heart, would it kill
him?'' Jenoff said in a July 27 interview in the Camden County
prosecutor's office. ''And I said I really don't know. I said they
have new models with like 200,000 volts, it probably would, but
mine is an old model.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff said Neulander suggested that Levin be attacked outside
his Route 70 business or a gym in Cherry Hill. Jenoff claims he
turned down the rabbi's request, and suggested Neulander was in
enough trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff also claimed Neulander once asked if a stun gun could be
used to kill Mrs. Neulander.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said, no, it would just knock her out ... for probably three
to five minutes,'' Jenoff said during the interview.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff did not specify when the alleged statements about the
stun gun took place.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Zucker, one of the attorneys representing Neulander,
said Jenoff's comments ''were as incredible as everything else he's
said.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff's attorney said he had not read his client's statement.
Levin's attorney, Jaime Kaigh, could not be reached for comment. An
answering service at Kaigh's office said Saturday that Kaigh would
be unavailable until Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
