<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BIC to sue N.J. company over national lighter recall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MILFORD, Conn. (AP) - Bic Corp. announced Saturday that it will
file a lawsuit against a New Jersey company accused of illegally
importing 294,000 BIC lighters for sale in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Vaid Enterprises of Jersey City, N.J., is recalling the lighters
because young children could ignite them, the U.S. Consumer Product
Safety Commission said. The lighters, made by Milford-based BIC,
lack federally required child-resistant mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the company nor the agency is aware of any injuries
involving the lighters, the product safety commission said. CPSC
announced the recall on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The recalled lighters are gray goods, meaning they were never
intended for sale in the U.S., and were illegally brought into this
country by Vaid Enterprises,'' said Thomas M. Kelleher, senior vice
president-administration and general counsel for BIC. ''The
recalled lighters were produced in a BIC factory in France for sale
in markets outside the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   BIC plans to file the lawsuit next week, said Linda K. Kwong, a
company spokeswoman. She could not say where the lawsuit would be
filed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to take a real aggressive posture with the importer,''
Kwong said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelleher said BIC has brought lawsuits in federal court against
importers of gray market BIC lighters.
</P>
<P>
   ''BIC aggressively approaches stores that are selling illegally
imported products to find the source of the product and, where
appropriate, we pursue legal action against the importers and
distributors,'' Kelleher said.
</P>
<P>
   Vaid could not be reached for comment Saturday. The company is
not listed in the telephone directory. A number supplied by BIC was
outdated.
</P>
<P>
   The disposable lighters being recalled are oval-shaped ''BIC''
and mini-''BIC'' brand lighters. They have a green, red, blue,
black or yellow body; a metal top; and do not have a metal shield
over the sparkwheel.
</P>
<P>
   The standard size lighters have the UPC number 3 086120 600020.
The mini-lighters have the UPC number 3 086120 600051.
</P>
<P>
   Convenience, gas, grocery and thrift stores in the East sold the
lighters from January through April for about $1 each.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers should stop using these lighters immediately and
return them to the place of purchase for a refund.
</P>
<P>
   The recall does not involve lighters sold by BIC in the U.S.,
which all comply with the CPSC child-resistant standard.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, consumers should call the CPSC at
1-800-638-2772.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Bic: http://www.bicworldusa.com
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Product Safety Commission: http://www.cpsc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
