<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Israeli Conductor Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Israeli conductor David Shallon, a one-time
assistant of Leonard Bernstein at the New York Philharmonic who
went on to lead orchestras around the world, died in Tokyo after
suffering an asthma attack. He was 49.
</P>
<P>
   Shallon, in Japan to conduct the Tokyo Metropolitan Symphony
Orchestral, was rushed to a hospital following the Friday night
attack and pronounced dead soon thereafter, Kyodo News agency said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The conductor, who until recently was musical director of the
Jerusalem Israel Broadcasting Authority Orchestra, came to Japan in
early September for concerts with the Tokyo group.
</P>
<P>
   Shallon's wife, violist Tabea Zimmermann, had performed in the
Tokyo concerts as a soloist, associates in Israel said. The two
often performed together.
</P>
<P>
   ''Shallon was at a very promising stage of his career,'' said
Gidon Paz, who served as the IBA orchestra's managing director
while Shallon was musical director.
</P>
<P>
   He said Shallon was promoted new music and was especially
helpful in giving voice to upcoming Israeli composers by providing
venues for their music to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   Shallon worked closely with the late conductor Leonard Bernstein
throughout the years and served as his assistant at the New York
Philharmonic in the 1970s, Paz said.
</P>
<P>
   Shallon was currently serving as conductor of the Luxembourg
Symphony Orchestra and had homes both in Tel Aviv and in a small
town outside of Frankfurt, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Shallon studied at the Vienna Academy of Music. He went on to
conduct at orchestras around the world including the Dusseldorf
Symphony, the Berlin Philharmonic, the London Symphony, and the San
Francisco Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   The Tel Aviv-born Shallon is survived by his wife and their
two-year-old son Yuval.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-16-00 2037 </TRAILER>
