<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officials weigh spraying to fight West Nile virus  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Garrison, a leader in the small rural community of Hebron,
suddenly finds himself making a potentially life-and-death
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Garrison and officials from Columbia and Lebanon met Saturday
with residents to discuss plans to spray a pesticide to fight the
West Nile virus. The meeting was held in Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Environmental Protection is recommending
spraying in a two-mile radius covering those towns as well as in
Milford, Bethel and Danbury.
</P>
<P>
   The spraying would not begin until Wednesday at the earliest,
DEP officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation comes after horses in Danbury, Hebron and
Milford were diagnosed with the West Nile virus, the first cases of
infection in mammals in the state this year.
</P>
<P>
   The horses in Hebron and Danbury were euthanized on Aug. 30 and
Sept. 7. The horse in Milford became sick on Sept. 5, but is
recovering, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents are concerned about the effects of the
pesticides. Garrison said he understands those concerns, but he is
worried that a lack of spraying could lead to human fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to be sitting here a month from now lamenting why
we didn't spray and we have some fatalities,'' Garrison said.
</P>
<P>
   While Garrison wants to spray, Joyce Okonuk, first selectman in
Lebanon, wants more information after hearing the residents'
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ''At this point, I haven't decided. I want to learn more,''
Okonuk said.
</P>
<P>
   A phone conference is planned Monday between the DEP and
officials from Columbia, Hebron and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The DEP has a preliminary agreement with officials in Milford,
Bethel and Danbury to spray, said Michele Sullivan, a spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ''The state takes the recommendation for spraying very
seriously,'' Sullivan said. ''Any pesticide has a risk, but this
pesticide poses a low risk to humans.''
</P>
<P>
   The risk of human transmission is higher now because the type of
mosquitoes which bit the horses also bite humans, Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the highest risk we've ever seen for West Nile virus
in Connecticut,'' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that risk remains low, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   No human cases of the mosquito-borne disease have been reported
in Connecticut this summer, but infections have been reported in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Children, the elderly and people with weakened immune systems
are most at risk.
</P>
<P>
   West Nile virus can cause a range of flu-like symptoms. In the
most serious cases, infection can result in encephalitis, or
swelling of the brain, which can lead to death.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, about 130,000 mosquitoes have been trapped around
the state and tested at the Agricultural Experiment Station.
Infected bird-biting mosquitoes were found earlier this summer in
Stamford and Norwalk. The state also has found the virus in 279
dead birds in 47 different municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   ''West Nile virus is back with a vengeance this year. It is much
more widespread than any of us expected it would be,'' said
Theodore Andreadis, head of the mosquito testing program at the
Connecticut Agricultural Experiment Station.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-16-00 2109 </TRAILER>
