<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAS: Peru Should Suspend Spy Chief  </HEADLINE>
By MONTE HAYES
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- The Organization of American States demanded
Saturday that the government of President Alberto Fujimori suspend
Peru's intelligence chief and other officials allegedly involved in
the bribing of an opposition legislator.
</P>
<P>
   The strongly-worded demand came as opposition parties increased
their calls for Fujimori, who was re-elected in a controversial
vote earlier this year, to step down and allow new elections.
</P>
<P>
   The OAS said that opposition groups had informed the
organization that unless intelligence chief Vladimiro Montesinos
were fired, they would not join OAS-sponsored talks with the
government on strengthening democracy in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations ''are of the utmost seriousness'' and require
the government to ''respond with quick and severe actions which
result in the suspension from public duties of those accused,'' the
OAS said in a statement released in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ''Given the numerous accusations'' against Montesinos in recent
months, it would be difficult to move ahead with the OAS-sponsored
democracy talks ''if prompt action is not taken,'' the OAS said.
</P>
<P>
   Montesinos, Fujimori's closest adviser and the feared head of
the National Intelligence Service, was seen in a video released
Thursday apparently bribing opposition congressman Alberto Kouri to
support the government.
</P>
<P>
   The 56-minute video, which had poor sound quality, showed Kouri
signing a document that apparently formalized his resignation from
the opposition. Montesinos then handed Kouri what seemed to be a
thick wad of bills.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the broadcast was broadcast Thursday night, Kouri
said the meeting with Montesinos had been to discuss matters of
national security. Hours later, he admitted having received $22,500
from Montesinos -- but said it was a loan to buy a truck to
distribute food to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Montesinos has been accused of illicit
enrichment and engineering smear campaigns against Fujimori's
opponents in this year's presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   The political storm over the bribery allegations came as
Fujimori was trying to repair damage to his image abroad from
charges of widespread fraud in his election to an unprecedented
third term in May.
</P>
<P>
   Although Fujimori's political alliance won only 52 seats in the
120-member Congress in May, a dozen opposition congressmen quickly
joined the government's ranks, giving Fujimori majority control.
</P>
<P>
   Alejandro Toledo, who pulled out of the May presidential runoff
after charging Fujimori planned to rig the results, later accused
the government of offering congressmen elected on his ticket
$50,000 and upwards to join Fujimori's alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Olivera, the opposition congressman who released the
tape, said Saturday that Fujimori's vice president, Francisco
Tudela, should head a transition government and call new elections
within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Javier Valle Riestra, a constitutional expert and a former prime
minister in the Fujimori government, urged Congress to shorten
Fujimori's five-year term to one year and call ''truly free
elections.''
</P>
<P>
   He also criticized Fujimori for not speaking out since the video
scandal erupted. ''If Fujimori remains silent, he is going to be
dragged down by this crisis,'' Valle Riestra said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-16-00 2140 </TRAILER>
