<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gay Army Reservist Fights for Job  </HEADLINE>
By LEON DROUIN KEITH
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ALAMITOS, Calif. (AP) -- The Army started making its case
Saturday to dismiss reserve Lt. Steve May, the Arizona legislator
accused of violating the military's ''don't-ask, don't tell'' by
running for office as an openly gay candidate.
</P>
<P>
   May, whose military record is unblemished, wants to finish the
last seven months of his Army commitment.
</P>
<P>
   He argues that while he spoke of his homosexuality as a citizen
and as a public servant, he never spoke of it while actively
serving in the Army. He was honorably discharged in 1995 and not
recalled to active duty until February 1999 in preparation for
possible deployment to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The government contends May was on active status as a reservist
when he acknowledged his sexual orientation during a legislative
debate the same month, even though he had not been yet been called
to duty.
</P>
<P>
   Army attorneys also suggested that May's interviews about his
case on ''Larry King Live,'' ''60 Minutes'' and in a cover story
for Newsweek violated his military duty, May's attorney Christopher
Wolf said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think that's an absurd argument,'' Wolf said.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of three colonels is hearing the case at the Army base
in this Orange County suburb south of Los Angeles and could finish
as early as Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Army attorneys declined to discuss the specifics of the case,
and May requested the hearing be closed.
</P>
<P>
   In his case, instead of seeking a dishonorable discharge, as is
more common in ''don't ask, don't tell'' cases, the Army attorneys
are seeking a general discharge. A dishonorable discharge would
prevent May from getting benefits and being able to re-enlist; a
general discharge is benign.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf said the Army spent much of Saturday morning establishing
what both sides already agree upon: May is gay.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the panel believes May violated the ''don't ask, don't
tell'' policy, the colonels could allow him to remain in uniform
under a Defense Department provision by declaring the action was
for the good of the military, Wolf said.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Walter C. Herin Jr., deputy staff judge advocate for
the 63rd Army Regional Support Command supervising May's unit, said
that is just one of five provisions May would have to meet.
</P>
<P>
   May also would have to show that his homosexual conduct is a
departure from his usual behavior, that it is unlikely to occur,
that he has not forced homosexual acts on someone else and that he
does not intend to engage in such acts in the future, Herin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Army began investigating May after he acknowledged his
sexuality during a legislative hearing on a state bill that would
have prohibited government benefits for employees' gay partners. He
had been open about his homosexuality since his first campaign for
elected office in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   An investigator recommended May be discharged, though his report
recommends May's commanders consider his performance first. May has
been rated an exceptional officer.
</P>
<P>
   Los Alamitos is the headquarters for the Army 63rd Regional
Support Command, which oversees May's unit, the 348th
Transportation Company.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the first full year of ''don't ask, don't tell,''
discharges totaled 617.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Army: http://www.army.mil/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
