<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressIda Drapkin:
<TEXT>
<P>
   RANCHO PALOS VERDES, Calif. (AP) -- Ida Drapkin, an amateur
horticulturist whose development of more than 30 hybrids of the
colorful fuchsia plant brought her international recognition, died
Wednesday of cancer. She was 78.
</P>
<P>
   Drapkin developed dozens of hybrids. At one time, she said, her
back yard was filled with as many as 3,000 fuchsia plants.
</P>
<P>
   She handed out fuchsia-colored business cards, ran a small
business selling plants and fuchsia-inspired merchandise, including
her own line of clothing, and served as president of the National
Fuchsia Society.
Grace Hartley Germon:
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Grace Hartley Germon, food writer and editor of
The Atlanta Journal and Journal-Constitution Sunday magazine for 35
years, died Thursday of respiratory failure. She was 95.
</P>
<P>
   Germon joined the Journal in 1936 and founded the first National
Food Editors Conference in 1944, a precursor of today's Association
of Food Journalists. She published ''Grace Hartley's Southern
Cookbook'' in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Always open to innovations, Germon had the first microwave oven
model installed at her Lithonia home. She also helped readers
incorporate the new frozen foods into their menus.
Miguel Sepulveda:
</P>
<P>
   RENO, Nev. (AP) -- Nevada newspaper publisher and Hispanic
activist Miguel Sepulveda died Friday following an asthma attack.
He was 59.
</P>
<P>
   Sepulveda founded northern Nevada's Spanish-language newspaper
Ahora in 1983 with his wife, Sheila, and distributed it in Hispanic
hangouts across the state.
</P>
<P>
   Sepulveda also founded the Northern Nevada Hispanic Chamber of
Commerce, Reno's Salsa and Latin Jazz Festival and wrote the
original grant application for what is today known as Nevada
Hispanic Services, a non-profit agency serving northern Nevada's
Hispanic community.
David Shallon:
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Israeli conductor David Shallon, a one-time
assistant of Leonard Bernstein at the New York Philharmonic who
went on to lead orchestras around the world, died Friday after a
severe asthma attack. He was 49.
</P>
<P>
   The conductor headed the Luxembourg Symphony Orchestra and until
recently was musical director of the Jerusalem Israel Broadcasting
Authority Orchestra. He came to Japan in early September for
concerts with the Tokyo Metropolitan Symphony Orchestral.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Shallon worked closely with the late conductor
Leonard Bernstein throughout the years and served as his assistant
at the New York Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   Shallon had also conducted orchestras around the world including
the Dusseldorf Symphony, the Berlin Philharmonic, the London
Symphony and the San Francisco Symphony.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
