<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Theft suspect accidentally shot by trooper  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   GREENWICH, N.Y. (AP) - A 21-year-old man suspected of stealing a
car ended up with a bullet in the buttocks when a state trooper's
gun accidentally went off, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on a report by a woman who heard someone steal her car
out of her driveway about 1:30 a.m. Saturday, a state trooper saw
the car at a nearby intersection. As the trooper approached the car
on foot, the driver put the car in motion, hitting the trooper and
knocking him off balance.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the trooper's gun accidentally went off, the bullet
passing through the door of the car and hitting Phillip K. Boyce.
Boyce drove about a mile before crashing the car. He was stuck in
the car and had to rescued by firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   He was taken to Albany Medical Center where he remained Saturday
night in police custody, charged with felony counts of assault,
reckless endangerment and possession of stolen property and a
misdemeanor count of driving while intoxicated.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation into the shooting is continuing. The trooper
was not identified.
</P>
</TEXT>
