<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-16 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dead in I-77 crash members of one family  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   STATESVILLE, N.C. (AP) - Five members of a Yadkin County family
were killed in the fiery collision along Interstate 77 in Iredell
County caused by an inattentive driver, the Highway Patrol said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The victims were riding in a 1989 Dodge minivan that was hit in
the rear Friday afternoon by a tractor trailer, setting off a chain
of collisions that involved three other cars, said Trooper Todd
Keller.
</P>
<P>
   No charges had been filed yet, but Keller said he planned to
talk to prosecutors Monday and expected there to be charges in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Victims were identified as the driver, Mickey Dean Blackburn,
47, of Boonville in Yadkin County. Passengers in the van were his
wife, Christine Kimmer Blackburn, 38, and their children: Mikki
Blackburn, 2; Bobbi Kimmer, 4, and Destiny Kimmer, 5.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just so sad, to take five people out of my family,'' Fay
Kimmer, the mother of Christine Blackburn, said Saturday. ''I
definitely I want to know that it was quick, that there was no
suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Rick Barrett of the Highway Patrol said the cause of the
accident, which occurred where the interstate narrowed from two
lanes to one, appeared to be inattention by the truck driver.
</P>
<P>
   ''He just came up on that traffic and wasn't paying attention
and ran right over them,'' Barrett said. ''We have no indication of
mechanical trouble or that the driver was impaired.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett said speed didn't appear to be a major factor.
</P>
<P>
   Truck driver William Robin Townsend, 41, of Hudson, was treated
for minor injuries and released. He was driving an empty truck for
Merchants Distributors of Hickory, Barrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Three members of a New Jersey family, who were in the second
car, were taken to area hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Woodward, 68, of Randolph, N.J., was in serious condition
Saturday night in the burn unit of Baptist Medical Center in
Winston-Salem Baptist. His daughter, Lee Ann Standridge, 21, was
treated and released from the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Woodward, Edward Woodward's wife and the driver of the
car, was treated and released from Iredell Memorial Hospital in
Statesville.
</P>
<P>
   The accident happened about five miles north of Statesville
about 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The accident happened near a construction zone, but that the
cars and tractor-trailer had not yet reached it.
</P>
<P>
   The burning mini-van was lodged underneath the tractor-trailer,
witnesses said.
</P>
</TEXT>
